[{'created': '2013-10-31 05:12:13.000000000', 'message': "sync log from oslo

5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig
fb8075a19d Add amqp=WARN,qpid=WARN to default_log_levels
4654a5d247 Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging
41ddd7a975 _get_log_file_path explictly return, when logfile/logdire unset
e12e6b45f8 Make openstack.common.log Python 3 compatible
572cfecb4d Make Messages unicode before hitting logging
3243cdfbe9 python3: handle module moves in log

DocImpact

Change-Id: I63e21a4fbcc633e68a37a549508f971ac0704a6f
"}]
commit_message:
sync log from oslo

5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig
fb8075a19d Add amqp=WARN,qpid=WARN to default_log_levels
4654a5d247 Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging
41ddd7a975 _get_log_file_path explictly return, when logfile/logdire unset
e12e6b45f8 Make openstack.common.log Python 3 compatible
572cfecb4d Make Messages unicode before hitting logging
3243cdfbe9 python3: handle module moves in log

DocImpact

Change-Id: I63e21a4fbcc633e68a37a549508f971ac0704a6f

Use nova.conf for auth_token configs.

Updates lib/nova so that we use the application config file (nova.conf)
instead of the Nova api-paste.ini config file.

Related-Bug #1240753

commit_message:
Fix the old url for own repository

 In HACKING.rst, there is a url for own repository. However that is old
url. So we get 404 error if we access it.
 This commit fixes it.

Change-Id: I6109310c76e4abe78d30febe2cbce3c3881ae6d5

commit_message:
Source apache in keystone upgrade script

Keystone in devstack has added the ability to work with apache. Grenade
needs to source the lib/apache file to provide the functions required to
make these checks.

Change-Id: Ica26da300a9682484871a7aefe9e38ef8bbf3c48

[{'created': '2013-10-31 10:27:52.000000000', 'message': "Fix image file path of upgrade-tempest

 Currently, boto's 's3_materials_path' and scenario's 'img_dir' of
tempest.conf values are incorrect because the global variable of FILES
is not set and not passed to the devstack's configure_tempest().
 This commit fixes it to be set the proper value.

Change-Id: Ic926d8776155a580fd84ad8d2d49b6007954de4f
"}]
commit_message:
Fix image file path of upgrade-tempest

 Currently, boto's 's3_materials_path' and scenario's 'img_dir' of
tempest.conf values are incorrect because the global variable of FILES
is not set and not passed to the devstack's configure_tempest().
 This commit fixes it to be set the proper value.

Change-Id: Ic926d8776155a580fd84ad8d2d49b6007954de4f

commit_message:
Use cinder.conf for auth_token configs.

Updates lib/cinder so that we use the application config file (cinder.conf)
instead of the Cinder api-paste.ini config file.

Related-Bug #1240753

Change-Id: I6636d33ee522757145ac97fc354324a8b9379700

commit_message:
Initial implementation of service_catalog panel.

Implemented getting list of services, actions 'Toggle Active',
'Download Service', 'Delete Service'.

Action 'Upload Service' is implemented, but currently does not
work properly.

Action 'Compose Service'/'Modify Service' is under construction as
well as the corresponding form. 'Metadata Objects' table (which can be
accessed from 'Compose Service' form) is yet to come.

Change-Id: I37e411fba01819a5d4a61978a283bcb6a45f2e55

BSD mktemp requires a template for the file/directory name.
GNU mktemp supports the option, but is not mandatory.

This change passes in the template, so that the check_uptodate.sh is

Closes-Bug: 1246858
'}]
commit_message:
Make check_uptodate compatible with BSD shells

BSD mktemp requires a template for the file/directory name.
GNU mktemp supports the option, but is not mandatory.

This change passes in the template, so that the check_uptodate.sh is
more compatible across different environments.

Change-Id: Id4abb92054363416272f583600e3d8ff2a9f9d42
Closes-Bug: 1246858

commit_message:
Recommend vCenter VMDK driver and other edits

Updated the VMware VMDK driver doc to recommend the vCenter VMDK
driver since the ESX VMDK driver has not been tested extensively.
Also made other edits to make the document easier to read.

backport: havana

Fixes bug #1246913

Change-Id: Iae910c59d0950cb19d18cded6a99842a1cbfd8b6

commit_message:
Remove superflous 'instances' joinedload

We already specify instances.{system_metadata,info_cache} as columns to
join so, loading 'instances' is implicit joinedload_all() behaviour.

Change-Id: I0c28e3b4d2ce8b5884d1247a7f96ecc810842d93

commit_message:
Enable Neutron FWaaS service

I added tempest case in below commit but
Jenkins failed.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51529/

This commit enables Neutron FWaaS service
in devstack to make sure Jenkins will not
fail.

[{'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-07-31 14:53:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-07-31 14:53:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-08-01 01:59:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Since this is a draft, the rest of the world cannot read or review. I think it is better to be seen by a wider audience'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2013-08-01 18:02:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (9 inline comments)

Good starting point.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-01 22:28:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (9 inline comments)

Answers to your queries below'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-08-02 00:09:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (2 inline comments)

So i'm not so keen on using the auth mechanism as a query mechanism like that, especially when the control goes to an extension mechanism (though i'm prepared to be overruled). 

In terms of discussion what i think would better suit the extension format: 

Steps 1 & 2 can be combined and put at GET /OS-FEDERATED
I'm not sure if there is a need for both given the optimal case will be always retrieving both but guang's /OS-FEDERATED/protocol and /providers can work there. 

Step 3 can be at GET /OS-FEDERATED/provider_id (or possibly included in the return from Step 1/2)

Step 4 at POST /OS-FEDERATED/protocol (? that seems wrong, but there should be a logical choice here) 

Step 5 continues at POST /auth/tokens and returns a valid token. 

That's purposefully fairly vague and just an idea, but i prefer that a 401 from /auth/tokens is a real failure and it will work into the current auth scheme better. Also i agree that it should be an extension, so we may as well exploit the freedom that that gives."}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2013-08-05 12:57:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I don't agree with you about Steps 3-5.

We assumed that the AdditionalAuthRequired exception was the correct way to indicate further communication is required to complete authentication in a multi stage authentication process, such as federated authentication. I would prefer all of the protocol specific functionality to be in one module as I think this makes extending the plugin to support more protocols much simpler.

That being said, I could appreciate the idea of moving the discovery service (steps 1 and 2) but I don't see a use case for it outside of federation, so this is why we chose to add it as a pre-auth stage to the federated authentication process. If people feel strongly however, I would not object to changing this."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-08-05 18:57:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (6 inline comments)

Jamie has the right approach.  In addition, there is no reason that the URL to get a token for federation has to be under /auth.  I would recommend that that also be kept under the OS-FEDERATED  sub URL. It will actually make it easier to understand if all of the resource are inside one suburl.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-08-05 18:57:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2013-08-07 01:05:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(8 inline comments)

Some copy changes that might make things a bit easier to read."}, {'account_id': 7662, 'date': '2013-08-07 21:13:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-07 21:43:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Several of you have misunderstood the auto-provisioning feature. If the user already exists in the Keystone user database then of course there is no need to auto-provision the user. The existing entry can be used. All that is needed is for the user to login via his existing Keystone entry and then via his federated IDP and Keystone can link the two identities together. But in many (most?) federation cases, the users will be already known to the IDP but not to the cloud service provider (who may have been given a contract to provide services to the IDP's users, so the cloud service provider leaves it up to the IDP to decide who they are). In this case the users need to be auto-provisioned. It does not make sense to manually populate Keystone with the user entries.

Auto-provisioning does not end up polluting the name space since the IDs used in federation are globally unique. They have to be, otherwise two different federated users would have the same identifiers, and the system would be broken. (Just as in SMTP, no two users can have the same email addresses). So I dont understand where the idea of name space pollution came from.

Concerning a user having multiple identities (which equates to different accounts at different IDPs) then to the federated system he is multiple different users. Just as you can have two different email accounts today (say at Google and Yahoo, you are two different email users as far as SMTP is concerned). So there is no problem with this is there? The problem only arises if the user wishes to use multiple different IDP accounts to login to the "same" Keystone account. We could simply rule this out (just as Google and Yahoo wont synchronise their emails) or we could use technology that we have already built and tested in our account linking service to allow users to link multiple accounts together (we have a public demo and published papers on this if you are interested.) But I suggest in the first version we rule out multiple IDP account linking for the purposes of simplicity'}, {'account_id': 7662, 'date': '2013-08-08 13:24:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

What I mean by pollution is that a user may have multiple Federated IDs (for whatever reason). With auto-provisioning they will be treated as unique users (as you say, the are globally unique). So one guy could have multiple Keystone logins, each with different roles, etc. This may be desirable, but users may find it confusing.

This also crosses over into questions about what the default rights will be for an auto-provisioned user, and how fine-grained they will be.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-08 14:41:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Rob I dont understand what your criticism in federation is. If a user has multiple accounts, so what? That is up to the user. If the user wants to access the cloud from two different IDP accounts as two different users, so what? That is his choice. Why would a user find it confusing to login via different identities and potentially get different privileges? Surely he would expect this to be the norm. 

I would argue that if a user logged in via different accounts and was seen to be exactly the same user, he would think "this is spooky, how did the system know that user A is the same as user B. I never told it they were both me".

Concerning authorisation rights and default rights, this is a separate issue. The authz rights are set by configuration and can be as fine grained as the admin wants them to be. Admin can give all users the same rights or all users different rights. So I dont believe this is an issue'}, {'account_id': 7060, 'date': '2013-08-08 14:52:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Daivd,
I think what Rob aimed at ws that some users may want to be able to configure their first 'openstack autocreated user' to be the a mapping for multilpe identities.

No spooky thing, the user would be the one to add more identities to the mix.

I.E. it would be the user's choice to configure his own account to amp multiple users. Although I think this would be a nice to have, I think managing it from an admin PoV would be hard, how do you then prevent users to allow random other individuals to login as themselves by simply adding their ID there ? The amount of verification process around allowing such a thing would be quite an implementaiton burden. However should someone want to do it it would be nice to have as an option not enabled by default."}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-08 15:12:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Simo,

As I said in a previous post, we have already implemented account linking. A public demo of this is available here

https://persistence.kent.ac.uk/logins4life/

Here a user can link his Facebook account to his Google account to his Kent account in order to access the same services at Kent (these are not cloud services but they could have been).

But again as I said in a previous post, I think account linking should be an advanced feature that is not part of the initial federation specification.

Several European academic communities have been using federation for many years, and none of them have yet implemented account linking. So it is not a low hanging fruit.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-08 16:07:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-08 16:46:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

Build succeeded.

'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-08-08 22:01:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(6 inline comments)

You are misunderstanding the basica approach of REST here.  Keystone extensions are different from AUTH PLUGINS. What you want is an extension for discoverability, such as was done for trusts https://github.com/openstack/identity-api/blob/master/openstack-identity-api/v3/src/markdown/identity-api-v3-os-trust-ext.md

Each of the different calls should not be through one URL with different parameters, but should be top Level URLS.  Since this is a mult step process, each step should return the URL for the next step where appropriate.

Querying the list of supported protocols and the list of IdPs are useful tools, and should not be hidden away behind one RPC call."}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-08-09 06:42:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(5 inline comments)

I would like to keep the final step of actually being granted a token within /auth. I don't think it wise to advocate extensions having their own token issuing paths. The method will tell us there who to pass the data to.

What is the rationale behind providing a list of projects & domains within an unscoped token? I too have issues with the lack of information provided by an unscoped token but i don't know why this token should have more information than normal simply because it was issued by a federated protocol."}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-09 09:16:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I guess the fundamental disagreement is whether federation is seen as an extension to Keystone's functionality, like delegation/trusts, or whether federation is seen as another way of authenticating to Keystone ie. an alternative to local un/pw. We have viewed it as the latter, and therefore have designed federation to be pluggable like any other authentication module. Until this is resolved, we cannot agree on the right way to modify the API. In order to resolve this, consider for example, how is adding Kerberos authentication viewed? As an extension or another way of doing authentication. Similarly how is using PKI with external CAs, CRLs and OCSP servers viewed?"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-08-09 21:08:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

For now consider them extensions.  Trusts is an extension as well, and all of the new major features that are not just clean up of core functionality will start life as extensions as well.

PKI, Kerberos etc are not currently supported by Keystone per-se, but rather come from the Apache HTTPD container.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2013-08-11 09:21:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2013-08-11 09:22:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-08-11 23:59:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

So I think in many ways this is analogous to trusts. They are an extension but they still work there way into the main authentication path.

I tend to agree that we have (somewhat) pluggable authenticate for a reason and that we should be allowing things like federation to work in the auth path. What i disagree with is auth being used for discovery and the phase driven approach. 

I get the argument that federation is a multiple step authentication process and hence everything should go through auth. The practical way i see it working better here is that everything up until that final data packet and provider id is considered protocol specific negotiation and hence outside the scope of giving over my data in exchange for a token (Please note i said practical there and led with the sentence acknowledging I realize the theoretical issues).

In general here i think we should be embracing the extensions. They will provider a better means of discovery, and a much more tailorable approach for each protocol.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-12 11:09:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: (13 inline comments)

In summary, we appreciate the argument for making discovery an extension (or two extensions) and will make this change. But we do not agree with

a) splitting federated authn into part REST and part authn method (strongly opposed to this)

b) making federated authn a REST based protocol rather than another authn plugin. What is the purpose of having different authn plugins, if, when a new one appears, you don't want it to go there?"}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-12 16:28:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-12 16:49:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

I don;t think it makes sense to say that "federated" is a mechanism, but rather that we need internal helpers for the federation mechanisms.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-29 12:48:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

Hi Adam
Essentially there are two ways of approaching federation.
1. The one you suggest, which is ad-hoc, in which each federation protocol does its own thing and issues its own blueprint and API spec. There will be no or little common code and no or little common way of doing federation.
2. The one this spec suggests, which is a standard approach to federation, where there is a common framework for all federation protocols, a common API for all federation protocols, and common code to deal with the majority of federated authn and authz. Each federation protocol then specifies the specifics of how its uses the framework and common API, in a profile spec, and then its code can be simply plugged into the common code.

Maybe this high level discussion should be taken to the whole mailing list for a decision to be made about this?
regards
David'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-08-29 12:55:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: (1 inline comment)

Reply to Steve'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2013-08-29 16:54:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2013-05-17 15:46:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I'm fine on the principle of this capability, but think we need clarity about whether we are trying to limit to the impact of what a user do to be totally bound by the expiry time (see in line comment)"}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-05-17 15:52:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-05-17 15:56:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Ideally, the user should be able to do whatever permissions the roles that they have allow them to do.  A temporary user should be able to create a permanent user if policy allows.  Same with project, etc.

What is missing, and what is separate from this change, is how we are planning on enforcing such policy.  I don;t think the current policy mechanism is flexible for this.

Until we clarify these things, I think the most correct approach is to say that a temporary user cannot change the state of Keystone's Identity backends at all:  they cannot create projects, assign roles, or delete roles.  The sole exception should be that they can delete their own account. 

They should be able to modify credentials, but we are extracting credentials out of the id backend.

If we OK splitting out projects, roles, and role assignments, those should still be immutable to temporary users.

policy, and catalog continue to be unmodifiable."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-05-17 15:58:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Let me clarify:  what I wrote aboe is a good base policy set up, but does not need to be part of the API doc.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-17 16:01:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

We need to differentiate between administrators and end users.
1. End users cannot create other end users (as far as I know) so your comment does not apply to this situation
2. Administrators can create end users. An administrator could authenticate via federation and have a temporary entry created for himself, but nevertheless he may want to create a permanent user. This should be allowed. There is no difference between a permanent administrator creating a permanent user, and being fired immediately afterwards, and a temporary administrator creating a permanent user and his entry timing out. In both cases the user entry will exist and the administrator's entry will not.
3. If a temporary user delegates a permission to another user, then the duration of this delegation should not exceed the validity time of the temporary user's entry. Now this is a big topic that I dont think Keystone has properly addressed yet, because it can happen today (without temporary entries) that a user's token is about to expire and he delegates a permission to someone else. That permission should not exceed the time left in his token. But this is a bigger topic for discussion on the list I think"}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-05-17 16:05:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

You're both confusing deployment concerns with API concerns."}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-17 16:25:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: No score

What is the best way of getting a resolution of this issue?
The fundamental issues appear to be as follows:

1. a temporary user is given a token that is time limited to not exceed the lifetime of the user. Everyone agrees on this.

2. a temporary user can or cannot perform actions that may outlive him. There is disagreement on this one. Clearly it is possible for users in general to perform actions that outlive them. All parents know this :-). All presidents know this. If you create or edit a file in Swift it could last longer than your keystone entry. So my vote is that there should be no restrictions on what a temporary user can do whilst he has authority to do it.
Note that delegation of authority is different, because you are delegating your permissions to someone else. So clearly the delegated permissions cannot live for longer than your permissions.'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2013-05-17 16:25:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Dolph,

I'm confused about whether or not you think temporary users ought to be able to create permanent users. In your initial comment in patch 7 you seemed to say that they should only be able to create temporary users which won't outlive their own user, but in your comment in patch 9 it looks like you are saying something different (that temporary users should be treated as normal users while they exist?) Could you please clarify for me?

Thanks :)"}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-17 16:27:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Dolph can you please be more specific about what the API/deployment concerns are. I dont follow your logic
thanks'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-17 16:32:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Dolph said "whatever authorization you had simply goes away in either case (token expiration or user expiration)."
 
You are confusing authorisation with effect. Whilst your authz expires when your token or entry expires, the effect of this does not. It lives on. 

Dolph also said "the revised text brings up another issue though, in that this attribute should be described either being immutable, for simplicity"

not quite sure what you meant by this, but the expiry time can be updated and should be updated, say if the user refreshes his session before the existing one has timed out. His temporary entry should then be extended to the end of the new session'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-17 16:35:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Henry, you said "by this do you mean, for instance, that a temporary user could not update, say, the description of a permanent user?  What if the user creates a project?  Does that then have an expiry time too?  We probably need to be clearer what impact a temporary user can have."

I totally agree with your sentiment. My proposal as you can read above is that the authz permission only lives for the duration of the user's entry, but the effect of his authorised permissions can outlive him, and we should not try to artificially restrict any of them.'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2013-05-21 14:16:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-05-21 14:17:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- http://logs.openstack.org/29393/10/check/gate-noop/1763 : SUCCESS in 0s
'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2013-05-21 14:17:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Reverted `expires_at` description'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2013-05-21 14:50:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

One question on the expiry time"}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-21 14:59:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Henry, you are correct that privileges cannot be extended past the expiry time, but this was already agreed upon, and if I understand it correctly, it is already a feature of existing Keystone tokens. What is the change that you actually require to the patch to confirm this?

regards

david'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2013-05-21 15:11:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: (1 inline comment)

I think Henry's issue here is whether a user should ever be able to extend the lifetime of his own account. I've outlined my take on this in my inline comment."}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-21 16:40:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

The answer is obviously NO as this would be increasing a privilege'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2013-05-22 09:19:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-22 09:42:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Henry said not sure that's the total answer.  Since policy/permissions can only be specified on an api level (e.g. update_user), I am concerned that a common practice of allowing a user to update their own user record (without requiring an explicit role assignment - just the inclusion of user_id against update_user in the policy file) would therefore allow expiry to be modified by temporary users.  (This works by the fact that a user can get an un-scoped token which confirms they have authenticated, and the contents of such a token can then be used a part of a policy check on non-project things that relate to their identity, like change_password, update_user).

I see several possible solutions to this:
i) not allow the expires field to be a parameter of an update entry API request
ii) alter the policy checking code to ensure that expiry cannot be changed by the user
iii) one we split off Identity from Authz as Adam is proposing, then updating Identity attributes would not effect the Authz entry in Keystone. Since expiry is part of the authz entry and not the identity entry, then the problem simply dissappears once the identity backend split is implemented.

>Is there not a case for expiry time simply being immutable >(in the same way that the expiry time of a token is 
> immutable).

Yes we could do this, but prefer not to, since currently the federation code updates the expiry time if the user authenticates again before his previous session has expired. So it makes sense to update the expiry time of the entry to match the new session expiry. We could delete the entry and recreate it again with the latest time, but then any tokens from the old entry would become unusable, and we wanted to be able to handle a user having multiple parallel sessions to different OpenStack services.

So clearly we have to prevent users from updating this field, and limit it to the Fed code. Surely there must be a clean way of doing this in Keystone already."}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-05-23 06:28:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I'm not giving a score as i've discussed this offline with David and Kristy and it is an optional parameter.

I don't think we should support this. I think that the concept of a user is a long lived entity and that restricting access to services based on an expiry time is what tokens do.

If further control on the availability of the user is required then this should be (somehow) defined by a quota. 

If administrators wish to have a means of cleaning up users that are no longer active or haven't logged in for a period of time then they should have their own policies that we can possibly support with a tool later on. Even if the table grows into the low millions of users I think it is better to keep the user records and make the keystone devs put indexes on what they want to query."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-05-30 16:01:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-05-30 20:37:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-05-31 18:15:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Do not merge

(1 inline comment)

I am not sure this is the right approach.  It seems that it is the role assignments that should be time based, not the user.  If role assignments have all expired, you can then clean up unused users.'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2013-05-31 21:21:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Temporary user should not be an API change. It should be a backend functionality.

With the pluggable token management layer, you can achieve your goal by providing your own identity driver and token provider.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2013-06-01 09:09:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-06-04 18:57:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Given the block/concerns contributing this to core, I'd suggest that this be reworked as a v3 API extension similar to TRUSTS, and implemented into keystone.contrib as discrete middleware."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-06-04 18:58:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

(assuming gyee's suggestion is not satisfactory)"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-06-12 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Increase heat's defaut template size

The default template size is too small to launch some stacks
in the heat-templates repository without modifying devstack.

Increase the limit to 32768.

Change-Id: Id8df643b0327b88b29002662d8eb46638cea0f81

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-15 20:11:04.000000000', 'message': "Add group key support

A requestor asking for a key for a target identified as a group object
will receive a group_key ticket.

Group keys are temporary keys with a limited timelife and are released
together with a generation number. Multiple keys with different generation
numbers may exist at the same time.

When no valid keys are found or if the only valid key has less than 10 minutes
of lifetime a new key is generated using the next available generation number.

Generation numbers grow monotonically.

Group keys can be retrieved useing the get_group_key call only by
requestors belonging to the group. A requestor is considered as beloging
to a group if the first part of the name is the same as the group.

Requestors must specify a valid generation number when requesting a group
key. The generation number is used to create the destination name by
postfixing it to the group name after a colon.

Example:
requestor: scheduler.xyz.example.com
destination: scheduler:123

The requestor is considered part of the scheduler group and asks for
a key of generation number 123. If that key exist it will be returned
encrypted with the requestor's key.

blueprint key-distribution-server
Change-Id: I013ae466d626c0a4737d475e1b42b183a88dbe83
Signed-off-by: Simo Sorce <simo@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add group key support

A requestor asking for a key for a target identified as a group object
will receive a group_key ticket.

Group keys are temporary keys with a limited timelife and are released
together with a generation number. Multiple keys with different generation
numbers may exist at the same time.

When no valid keys are found or if the only valid key has less than 10 minutes
of lifetime a new key is generated using the next available generation number.

Generation numbers grow monotonically.

Group keys can be retrieved using the get_group_key call only by
requestors belonging to the group. A requestor is considered as belonging
to a group if the first part of the name is the same as the group.

Requestors must specify a valid generation number when requesting a group
key. The generation number is used to create the destination name by
postfixing it to the group name after a colon.

Example:
requestor: scheduler.xyz.example.com
destination: scheduler:123

The requestor is considered part of the scheduler group and asks for
a key of generation number 123. If that key exist it will be returned
encrypted with the requestor's key.

blueprint key-distribution-server
SecurityImpact
Change-Id: I013ae466d626c0a4737d475e1b42b183a88dbe83
Co-Authored-By: Jamie Lennox <jamielennox@redhat.com>

Anne, what do you mean with a "new adventure"? I guess Sukhdev didn't understood this reference. Sukhdev, the guide offers different choices ("adventures") for setup.

I think Anne suggested this to be an additional description besides the existing ones - so not replacing OVS but a separate setup.'}, {'account_id': 6558, 'date': '2013-10-24 17:53:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Andreas, 

After reading your comment, I realize that perhaps I did not quite understand Anne's reference to new adventure. 
However, I am now a bit confused. If I understand it correctly, our official stance is that OVS and LB plugins are deprecated in Havana. Then, why would we want to keep any reference to those in the newer version of the documents? 
We are not saying that OVS and LB will not work, we are simply taking those references out of the documents. This way the folks who are already familiar with OpenStack, and are using it, continue to use it. But, for the folks who are "new" to OpenStack and want to get involved, why would we not want them to start with the latest information? 
Why polute their minds with deprecated information? 

-Sukhdev'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2013-10-24 18:15:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Reading the patch, I noticed one patch too many ;)"}, {'account_id': 6772, 'date': '2013-10-24 18:25:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"However, I am now a bit confused. If I understand it correctly, our official stance is that OVS and LB plugins are deprecated in Havana. Then, why would we want to keep any reference to those in the newer version of the documents?"

We live in a world where many users are still clinging to nova-network, so I don't think it's really that simple (and I know as a user I *hate* it when technical people make decisions like this, wave a magic wand, and pretend something never existed).

I don't think we should remove the OVS and LB content until it is actually unsupported.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2013-10-24 18:54:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Replaces assertEqual with assertTrue and assertFalse

In order to improve coding practices and be aligned to a standard,
self.assertEqual(...,True) statements where replaced with
self.assertTrue and self.assertFalse.

Change-Id: I8ef97edeeaefefdb2ad043cadd5bf289deab0c77
Closes-Bug: #1230127

commit_message:
Sync rpc fix from oslo-incubator

Sync the following fix from oslo-incubator:

76972e2 Support a new qpid topology

This includes one other commit, so that the above fix could be brought
over cleanly:

5ff534d Add config for amqp durable/auto_delete queues

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1178375
(cherry picked from commit a1fe496e1113737d0b133a64078bc45c485dd3b2)

Conflicts:
	etc/cinder/cinder.conf.sample

Change-Id: I1fd5aaf87ec87836df3e44e83247bf82301475f5

commit_message:
validate and recommend the cidr

Bug #1195974

It is hard to validate the CIDR typed in by user,
the simple way is to recognize only one and recommend it
if user's input is not the one.

(cherry picked from commit 53a66b299f18a7184972502b43441a5ad7b050fd)

Conflicts:
	quantum/tests/unit/test_db_plugin.py
	quantum/tests/unit/test_l3_plugin.py

Change-Id: Ic8defe30a43a5ae69c3f737094f866b36bb68f59

subject: Change the types of hypervisor_type and launched_on columns

So, you still have not answered my question about how the migration is working.  It honestly doesn't make sense to me, and I really would appreciate a breakdown of what it's doing, and why the generic "new_column" is the appropriate approach.  You might also answer the question: if you're later renaming "new_column" (which I don't see in the code, and thus my question), how do you deal with the fact that some databases don't support ALTER COLUMN, and sqlalchemy_migrate works around that by copying the table?'}, {'account_id': 8054, 'date': '2013-10-16 10:37:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 38:

@Kevin, for mysql and other databases VARCHAR can be accessed much faster than TEXT or CLOB because VARCHAR data is stored inline with the table. My migration is intended to increase the speed of access to some fields. Its work is to create a dump of the column, in case you somehow randomly, this column will be a long value greater than 255, then create a new column with the correct data type (VARCHAR (255)), it is copied from the value of the old column, the old column is removed and the new one is renamed (38 and 39 lines). All this is done for all selected fields. 152 is an example of migration, which was used in the same method.'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2013-10-16 15:40:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 38: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

@Michael, a lot of time to spend only once to run, the same tests are very fast.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2013-10-19 21:31:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 38:

Sorry, I'm having trouble parsing your comment. Are you saying that the expensive migration runs once and therefore is better than retaining the wrong data type?

While I agree with that, the slowness of the migration will be a problem for our larger deployments... Migrations happen with total downtimes, so a migration like this which might take tens of minutes to run is a big deal, especially as it happens in line with other migrations which might also be slow.

I think there is a balance here. The benefit of the change has to outweigh the cost of the migration."}, {'account_id': 8054, 'date': '2013-10-19 22:40:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 38:

commit_message:
Change the types of hypervisor_type and launched_on columns

The columns launched_on and hypervisor_type in the tables nova.instances
and nova.compute_nodes respectively have their type defined as Text
(sql TEXT or CLOB) instead of String (sql VARCHAR), even though the
length of the text there is usually small. For mysql and other
databases VARCHAR can be accessed much faster than TEXT
or CLOB because VARCHAR data is stored inline with the table.

This migration changes the type of the following columns:
 - nova.instances.launched_on
 - nova.compute_nodes.hypervisor_type
 - nova.shadow_instances.launched_on
 - nova.shadow_compute_nodes.hypervisor_type
from TEXT to VARCHAR(255)

bp db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: Ie930432d66148d35bdf3331d462579d9a4dd85d8

commit_message:

commit_message:
Handle VLAN interfaces with Linux IP wrapper

Check if the interface name contains '@' character and use the part
before that character as interface name.

(cherry picked from commit 202fe60b646429aabeb2ef8b1430a1ba9b356061)
Closes-Bug: #1240125

commit_message:
Fix L2pop to not send updates for unrelated networks

With this patch L2 population mechanism driver
sends updates only with ports related to the
network id of the port which is being updated.

(cherry picked from commit de24799696a8199b13223c2ca3820a9ef015bbe0)
Fixes bug: 1240744

Change-Id: If7d51ce26bf0d0837a00da07fe85f48d55e681c6

Use mock in test_policy

FakePolicyEnforcer is trying to imitate the real policy enforcer.
We don't need it in the test_policy tests.

fixes bug 1243902

commit_message:
Make ROOTDIR determination more robust

Remove unused CLIENTDIR and replace it with a TESTDIR
(pointing to rootdir/keystoneclient/tests) and use
normpath for determining the full path of rootdir.

This change is needed if keystoneclient/ is a symlink
and etc/ is in a different directory hierarchy.

Change-Id: Ice9165ef25ec0200ccfb50c2f2f3121a136652a2

commit_message:
PEP 8 Public and internal interfaces

Define which interfaces are public and which are internal based
on PEP 8.

For reference, PEP 8 section is here:
http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#public-and-internal-interfaces

Change-Id: I14233796b7838b78fbd355014478f3e326542966

[{'created': '2013-10-29 18:34:08.000000000', 'message': 'Adds more Debian specifics.

This patch adds a full new chapter about Debconf configuration
within the Debian package. It also removes the Ubuntu specifics
from the Debian documentation, and adds screenshots of Debconf

commit_message:
Adds more Debian specifics.

This patch adds a full new chapter about Debconf configuration
within the Debian package. It also removes the Ubuntu specifics
from the Debian documentation, and adds screenshots of Debconf
screens replacing the long procedures.

Note that this is still a work in progress, but I am sending it
for review anyway, so that others can start to comment already.
Namely, I need to finish the work on:
- Nova
- Horizon
- Neutron
- Heat
- Ceilometer
and add hyperlinks from all of the OpenStack services to the
debconf chapter.

Early comments very much welcome!

Change-Id: Ie3752c931131a5cb5c20af6e7411748058f92c0b

commit_message:
Use HTTP storage to test copy file functionality

The copy file functionality should be tested using Filesystem and HTTP
backend stores instead of S3 and Swift (requiring more configuration).

Closes-Bug: #1175940

Change-Id: I8c45598f2f004006f379861479f6f34150d0f649

commit_message:
Add Rackspace Cloud DNS Resource

This will be a temporary solution to have a resource for DNS until
Designate is incubated. Also currently work is in progress for a
new API for Designate.
Until then this will serve as a resource for Rackspace Cloud DNS.

Implements: blueprint rax-dns-resource
Change-Id: Ief0c478b9e40f6f9446b386243400f062a941a36

Fixes rally NovaServers.boot_server benchmark bug which occurs due to
invalid attribute reference of the classes nova client. This bug appears
to have been introduced when rally switched a dict based set of clients.

The updates herein also permit the boot_server benchmark to function if
no networks are created on the Cloud. In this case the boot call does
not pass down a nic to provision.

This commit also includes boot_server unit tests to provide (obviously)
missing coverage for the benchmark method.

Closes-Bug: #1246407

Change-Id: Id8ca25f5060074a57ff97f1bfa54454dcc30654f
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes rally boot_server benchmark bug

Fixes rally NovaServers.boot_server benchmark bug which occurs due to
invalid attribute reference of the classes nova client. This bug appears
to have been introduced when rally switched a dict based set of clients.

The updates herein also permit the boot_server benchmark to function if
no networks are created on the Cloud. In this case the boot call does
not pass down a nic to provision.

This commit also includes boot_server unit tests to provide (obviously)
missing coverage for the benchmark method.

Closes-Bug: #1246407

Change-Id: Id8ca25f5060074a57ff97f1bfa54454dcc30654f

Add .gitreview, setup.py and other infrastructure.

* .gitreview
* Disutils files
* tox configuration
* add .venv to ignore
* "mistral" package
* Sphinx documentation skeleton

'}, {'account_id': 6609, 'date': '2013-10-30 23:44:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

It would be nice to have a quick chat about what we should be adding to this given that the list is getting long and there's a lot of stuff in core that could potentially be added.

Should we keep adding to this /reviews page? If so, add an index to the top so projects are easier to find? If not, do we want to split out the project list and run it with different config files (ie - reviews, reviews-tripleo, reviews-python-clients)?

We run this every 15 minutes and so far it's not taking too long to generate yet, I ran this script on a cloud instance: 6m9.903s"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-31 01:49:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

That seems like something orthogonal to my patch? Perhaps file a bug/mail -dev to kick of that discussion, but my last attempt at this conflicted with a patch for horizon, so I'd like to land this rather than spin on discussion that isn't urgent."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-31 04:57:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-10-31 04:57:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-10-31 13:17:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

Looks reasonable. This does change our precedent a bit in that  client libraries (like python-tuskarclient) haven't typically been here in the past. The reason for this was simply to keep the report a bit leaner... only including core projects, etc. This also kept the LP API hits to a minimum.

If we include tuskarclient I feel like we might as well include novaclient, glanceclient, etc. too. At which point this report may well become an absolute free-for-all. We've probably got some organizational work to do in the HTML report (possibly adding tabs or a way to select subsets of OpenStack projects... TripleO stuff for example).

My main concern might be in the realm of performance.
I do hope the LP API is up to the task of handling the traffic as we continue to add projects to reviewday. We may well need to put in some caching at some point to avoid repeatedly asking the LP API for priority information. This would speed up subsequent reviewday runs as well.

Going ahead with the approval for now... noting that we may need to consider some client side caching in the future to be a good citizen. (perhaps we are already in violation here!)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-31 13:17:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified

Build succeeded.

- gate-reviewday-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/49/54649/2/gate/gate-reviewday-pep8/45e5bf8 : SUCCESS in 44s
'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-31 13:17:59.000000000', 'content': 'Change has been successfully merged into the git repository.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-31 18:00:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi, the LP daily API traffic report (When I left) was counting requests by the million. I very much doubt that a few thousand requests for open proposals will be a significant issue. If it is, I'm equally sure the LP ops will reach out to us."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-10-31 19:58:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

lifeless: cool. I still think caching might be in order here. Many of the LP requests can take 2-3 seconds each to complete (especially the BP requests).'}]

commit_message:
Remove lvm-thin pool_size config option

The pool_size config option when using thin LVM
is never actually checked/honored.  It's also unlikely
that users will want to do something other than use the
entire VG for their thin pool.

Rather than have the unused option going forward let's
remove it from the config and just go with the default
behavior of utilizing the entire Cinder VG.

For folks that would like to only use a portion of the
VG for some reason, they can do an lvcreate pool on their
own (just like we have them do for the VG itself) and get
the same flexibility that way.

This is done simply by:
lvcreate -T -L ${size} ${vg-name}/${vg_name}-pool

DocImpact

Change-Id: I3ef2cde433b8dd775b1873a0d6df165dd1945d8c

[{'created': '2013-10-29 01:43:12.000000000', 'message': "Move decision_maker() call into setUpClass

Previously the class level call of decision_maker() to detect certain
configuration details for the boto tests was mad in the class
definition. This has issues with unit testing because it requires a
functional config at import time for the file. This commit avoids this
restriction by moving this call into setUpClass for BotoTestCase which
won't try to execute decision_maker() at import.

Change-Id: I8abf4ae109576499fed6b31ae644c1bac58e3350
"}]
commit_message:
Move decision_maker() call into setUpClass

Previously the class level call of decision_maker() to detect certain
configuration details for the boto tests was mad in the class
definition. This has issues with unit testing because it requires a
functional config at import time for the file. This commit avoids this
restriction by moving this call into setUpClass for BotoTestCase which
won't try to execute decision_maker() at import.

Change-Id: I8abf4ae109576499fed6b31ae644c1bac58e3350

commit_message:
Remove unused DEFAULT_DOMAIN variable

The keystone.identity.backends.ldap.DEFAULT_DOMAIN
variable wasn't used.

The keystone.assignment.backends.ldap.DEFAULT_DOMAIN
was used, but should not have been, because we've
got a keystone.assignment.core.DEFAULT_DOMAIN.

Change-Id: I0f4bb0bd953a9ced8c3dfc46ea44ff0e377db082

[{'created': '2013-10-28 22:51:03.000000000', 'message': 'Uses fixtures for mox and stubs

commit_message:
Uses fixtures for mox and stubs

Fixtures use the much more reliable addCleanup instead of the tearDown.
They also allow us the only use fixtures in test classes that use then
instead of having the overhead for every test class.

Change-Id: Ifca4ecce0d66932282334d3e4db6d10a2921dbbb

commit_message:
Add ability to pull python-swauth from git repository

Distribution packaged versions of python-swauth can be very old.
Installing python-swauth-1.0.8 from gholt's GitHub repository
brings in the ability to set allow_overrides so that middleware
such as TempURL and FormPost work well with swauth

* Added attributes to allow toggling between distribution package / git
* Added attributes to specify repository and tagged revision
* Added conditional install based on above attributes
* Bumped metadata and CHANGELOG

Change-Id: I5eaafb8af9977939bbb7f5b68baf3c9cbac8be7c

commit_message:
proxy removed from identity and changed to assignment

The identity_api served as a proxy for calling the assignment_api
but it was suggested that this proxy should be removed and the calls
should be made directly to the assignment_api.

bug: #1220913

Change-Id: I20c461c06db22c03eb6d16399d1ca50999d053d5

commit_message:
Sync log from oslo

5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig
fb8075a19d Add amqp=WARN,qpid=WARN to default_log_levels
4654a5d247 Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging
41ddd7a975 _get_log_file_path explictly return, when logfile/logdire unset
e12e6b45f8 Make openstack.common.log Python 3 compatible
572cfecb4d Make Messages unicode before hitting logging
3243cdfbe9 python3: handle module moves in log

DocImpact

Change-Id: I2e565fd65a00f1c6dea830a09487de9f03cb5279

commit_message:
Fix default values so they work in a devstack run

This commit fixes errors with the default values used in config.py
Previously, an incorrect default could potentially be masked in a
gate run by putting the correct value in the sample config. However,
by moving to an auto-generated sample config file the defaults set
in config.py will be used, exposing these mismatches.

Partially Implements: blueprint config-cleanup

Change-Id: I55caeed2589d45337337b291d7131afdadf28bb8

commit_message:
Add api version detection to verify_tempest_config

This commit adds glance api version discovery to
verify_tempest_config.py. It will query the glance API to see which
API versions are available and then compare that to what is in the
config, pointing out any differences

Partially Implements: blueprint config-verification

Change-Id: Ie75f7f526d78b85a53ea4b0484e670d373d622ec

commit_message:
Add config feature verification script

This commit adds a new tool to tempest that will verify that API
queryable config options are set correctly. Right now the list of
options that are verified is very short. Later on additional checks
will be added to verify other services features when the tempest
clients for the other services get functions to query enabled
extensions.

Partially Implements: blueprint config-verification

Change-Id: Ie3b5fadd74460fb7199bff7046ec0efe37268b94

commit_message:
Add tests for LVM -cow clearing

Ensure that volume_clear for Thick LVM snapshot deletion
references the -cow device, and that it uses the LV instead
of the -cow device for ThinLVM.

These tests were written for a change to stable/grizzly --
but are applicable for general use here as well.

Related-Bug: #1245529
Change-Id: I380ad7832d558d9aa73a701cbf3acc35229e70ab

commit_message:
Decrease tempest BUILD_TIMEOUT

The BUILD_TIMEOUT is the generally used timeout option in tempest.

Almost never expected to any operation takes more than 60 sec,
the 400 sec is too match for timeout.
Changing the BUILD_TIMEOUT to 196 sec, it is still expected to be safe.

It can make faster the failing test jobs.

Change-Id: I7e7c767400ca448cb86d27b60a1229a2afa69726

commit_message:
Add base test class for unit tests

This commit adds a base test class for the tempest unit tests. The
base class uses fixtures to capture STDOUT and STDERR as well as
providing an interface to use mox to stubout tests.

Change-Id: Ia60cccd77cfb6489f888ff088351fe267115a22f

RunTimeError on tearDownClass explained

The RunTimeError appearance on the console frequently caused
confusion, so it's message now explains the situation in a more
verbosely.

commit_message:
Add compatibility for InstanceMetadata and primitives

Since the virt drivers instantiate InstanceMetadata manually,
this adds a bit of compatibility for primitive instance objects
until we have all of compute manager converted.

Change-Id: Ifb9ae7838300280895d63ffbd13337529b6d883c

commit_message:
ensure we don't boot oversized images

Since we can't generally shrink incoming images, add extra checks
to ensure oversized images are not allowed through.
All cases when populating the libvirt image cache are now handled,
including the initial download from glance, where we avoid
converting to raw, as that could generate non sparse images
much larger than the downloaded image.

* nova/virt/libvirt/utils.py (fetch_image): Allow passing through
of the max_size parameter.
* nova/virt/images.py (fetch_to_raw): Accept the max_size parameter,
and use it to discard images with larger (virtual) sizes.
* nova/virt/libvirt/imagebackend.py (verify_base_size): A new
refactored function to identify and raise exception to oversized images.
(Raw.create_image): Pass the max_size to the fetch function.
Also enforce virtual image size checking for already fetched images,
as this class (despite the name) can be handling qcow files.
(Qcow2.create_image): Pass the max_size to the fetch function,
or verify the virtual size for the instance as done previously.
(Lvm.create_image): Pass the max_size to the fetch function.
Also check the size before transferring to the volume to improve
efficiency by not even attempting the transfer of oversized images.
(Rbd.create_image): Likewise.
* nova/tests/fake_libvirt_utils.py: Support max_size arg.
* nova/tests/test_libvirt.py (test_fetch_raw_image):
Add a case to check oversized images are discarded.
* nova/tests/test_imagebackend.py (test_create_image_too_small):
Adjust to avoid the fetch size check.

Fixes bug: 1177830
Fixes bug: 1206081

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/test_imagebackend.py
	nova/virt/libvirt/imagebackend.py

Change-Id: Idc35fce580be4f74e23883d1b4bea6475c3f6e30

commit_message:
ensure we don't boot oversized images

Since we can't generally shrink incoming images, add extra checks
to ensure oversized images are not allowed through.
All cases when populating the libvirt image cache are now handled,
including the initial download from glance, where we avoid
converting to raw, as that could generate non sparse images
much larger than the downloaded image.

* nova/virt/libvirt/utils.py (fetch_image): Allow passing through
of the max_size parameter.
* nova/virt/images.py (fetch_to_raw): Accept the max_size parameter,
and use it to discard images with larger (virtual) sizes.
* nova/virt/libvirt/imagebackend.py (verify_base_size): A new
refactored function to identify and raise exception to oversized images.
(Raw.create_image): Pass the max_size to the fetch function.
Also enforce virtual image size checking for already fetched images,
as this class (despite the name) can be handling qcow files.
(Qcow2.create_image): Pass the max_size to the fetch function,
or verify the virtual size for the instance as done previously.
(Lvm.create_image): Pass the max_size to the fetch function.
Also check the size before transferring to the volume to improve
efficiency by not even attempting the transfer of oversized images.
(Rbd.create_image): Likewise.
* nova/tests/virt/libvirt/fake_libvirt_utils.py: Support max_size arg.
* nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_libvirt.py (test_fetch_raw_image):
Add a case to check oversized images are discarded.
* nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_imagebackend.py
(test_create_image_too_small): Adjust to avoid the fetch size check.

Fixes bug: 1177830
Fixes bug: 1206081
Change-Id: I3d47adaa2ad07434853f447feb27d7aae0e2e717

commit_message:
Fixes wrong Qpid protocol configuration

notify_qpid.py is suffering from the same issue as described in
launchpad bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo/+bug/1158807.
Instead of setting connection.transport, it is attempting to
set connection.protocol.

Fixes bug 1243821

Change-Id: Ice3e7ad917c158a5953475809f3f46f48fd6054d

commit_message:
VMware: booting multiple instances fails if image is not in cache

If a new image is loaded int glance and more than 1 instance
is created with that new image, all but the 1st will fail
as each image will either try to upload the image or will
"think" the image is there and not bother uploading it.
When they try to boot the boot will fail.  The fix is to
lock the following threads until the file upload is complete

Fixes: bug #1222948
Change-Id: I1afcda82be8259e185f6fdd1729bb42ca3a91c96

As I understand sqlalchemy and python, this code does not change history.  If anything it returns exactly the same types (ie. strings with lengths) but removes the likelihood of user error by fat-fingering a string # in the future.  

Changing across the board gives us a higher likelihood of everyone starting to use this as a standard.  If we do it moving forward it doesn't have as likely a chance to stick with everyone.  People will use past examples as future code modification methods unless we make explicit these types of changes  That can be difficult given the distributed nature of this project."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-28 17:33:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I've got no problem getting on the proper types (in fact, I think it's important). I just don't think it's reasonable to change history because the two engines you're testing end up with the same schema as a result. Put it into a new migration (even if it does nothing) and I think it's fine."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-10-30 17:24:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-10-30 17:28:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: No score

You know what, I see Ricks point, its just an alias and a code refactoring, in reality.

It does feel back touching the old migrations, but given we cut and paste from those, we should update those to the new alias.

Is there another aspect to the objection with this that I am not seeing?'}, {'account_id': 475, 'date': '2013-10-30 17:29:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Thanks for the comments all.

I'll re-propose this series such that it doesn't change existing migrations.

I may hold off until migration compaction lands just to avoid having to deal with so much changing at once."}, {'account_id': 475, 'date': '2013-10-30 17:38:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

John:

I think Sean and Dan have a valid concern here.

I disagree that we shouldn't ever change past migrations: we're doing that right now as do migration compaction! In fact, we're using that same schema-diff tool to ensure that nothing changes on MySQL or Postgres.

However, just because `types.UUID` is currently just an alias for `String(36)`, there's no guarantee that in the future it will remain that simple.

It might learn about Postgres' native UUID type, and we wouldn't want past migrations suddenly using that.

So probably should just continue w/ the unsightly String(36) in the old migrations."}, {'account_id': 475, 'date': '2013-10-31 17:36:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Abandoned'}]

Still working on it'}, {'account_id': 1298, 'date': '2013-02-06 16:38:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi all,

I'm finally getting around to this and I've got a question about Mark's suggestion to move the keyring changes out of cfg.py and into its own subclass of ConfigOpts.

I'm still trying to verify this but I'd like y'all's thoughts... I don't think having the keyring as a subclass of ConfigOpts will work for some of the substitutions that we need to do.  For example (from the blueprint) nova.conf might have:

sql_connection = mysql://nova:$db_nova_password@dbhost...:3306/nova

... where db_nova_password is pulled from the secure source.

If sql_connection is processed by cfg.py's ConfigOpts and db_nova_password is processed by a different instance that's a subclass of ConfigOpts, then the base Mapping class for sql_connection won't have the db_nova_password value in it to use as a substitution.  Like I said, I'm still trying to confirm this but does that sound correct?

In order to have the secure values available for substitution, we need to either have the secure subclass have its hooks into the ConfigOpts instance so that it shares its __cache, or we don't have a separate subclass in the first place. In the first approach, I'm not sure how the substitution can even trigger the secure class to go get its value into the __cache in the first place. It seems to me that if the substitution calls the ConfigOpts get method for a token value, even with a shared __cache between ConfigOpts and a secure subclass, there's no indication for the secure subclass to do its thing.  

Am I missing something?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-02-06 20:08:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I think you're right. The changes to _do_get() need to be in ConfigOpts unless the wrapper has a private way to ask a ConfigOpts instance for a value without performing substitution on it.

It looks like _do_get() could be abstracted to several independent backends (config file(s), command line options, and keyring). That would mean changing what you have to be less about a "secure" backend and more about a series of dynamically loaded backends, then talking to those backends with an API. I could see someone else coming along later and providing a zookeeper backend, for example.

Making the config backend dynamic introduces a bootstrapping problem of configuring the config parsers, but the config file and command line options should always be there so in practice that's not a big deal.'}, {'account_id': 1298, 'date': '2013-02-07 18:49:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hey Doug,

Thanks for the comments!

Just to make sure this isn't getting over engineered, do you think it's likely that folks are really going to need to chain together multiple sources? E.g. keyring *and* zookeeper? Or is it more likely that one user specified source (which could hit multiple backends if it wishes) would be enough? Personally, I think 95% of people won't use this at all.

Just want to make sure we're not building a palace when a log cabin will do. ;-)"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-02-07 20:59:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

No, I don't expect the backends to be chained. I was trying to describe a set of changes that wouldn't be so specific to the keychain/secure backend, though, since I thought Mark's objection was bringing that concept into the core."}, {'account_id': 1298, 'date': '2013-02-07 21:56:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hey Doug,

Sorry for the misunderstanding. ;-)

I guess I'm not getting what you were suggesting. Can you elaborate please?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-02-08 00:49:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Mark didn't seem to like the idea of hard-wiring knowledge of "secure" config storage into the ConfigOpts class. You pointed out that the ConfigOpts class needs to retrieve values from the keyring before any string interpolation is done on them. I think you're both right.

I was trying to propose a way to make the provide a "generic" way to have a source of configuration settings other than the standard file(s), into which you could plug a keyring implementation.

I don't think you need more than one backend at a time. However, I try to avoid special cases. We already have at least 2 sources for config setting sources (the files and the command line options). Those are implemented as "special cases" inside ConfigOpts, but could easily become part of a new pluggable configuration system. The benefits of moving the config file and command line option code into plugins are we don't have any special cases and we get two example implementations to help make sure the plugin API is (more) correct and not just useful for a keyring backend.

So, if a ConfigOpts instance managed a list of "configuration sources" that included "command line options" and "config files" by default, and then a configuration option allowed the user to activate other plugins as well, you could have a keyring backend added to the end of that list when users wanted it. The lookup logic in _do_get() would then change from all of the hard-coded logic it has now, to a loop that asks each of the sources for the value.

Implementing that is certainly more than you signed up for when you started the keyring backend implementation, but it seemed like a way to achieve the decoupling Mark wanted, get keyring support, and provide another potentially useful feature at the same time.'}, {'account_id': 1298, 'date': '2013-02-08 01:42:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Doug,

Thank you for your patience. Yes, I agree and it makes sense now. I'll see what I can do about the implementation. Alas, my day job is rearing its ugly head again so there may be some lag (couple of weeks?) before I get back to it.

Thanks again!

Ken"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-02-15 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Allow keyring for config based passwords

This change allows for the option to move passwords out of config files
and into some keyring supported repository. Please see the blueprint for
details.

Note that if you don't specify its usage, the default behavior is
exactly like it is today.

blueprint pw-keyrings

Added missing import of openstack.common.gettextutils's _ for I18N

Address comments from review.

Resubmit because of unrelated Jenkins failure (in DeferredVersionTestCase)

Change-Id: I7cc0812b3ae733550a211b60c64d1470a0f079c8

commit_message:
Changes driver method for notifications

Oslo.messaging.Transport is used as an abstraction to redirect function
calls to the configured driver. _send_notification called
self._driver.send instead of self._driver.send_notification

As the test
oslo.messaging.tests.TestTransportMethodArgs.test_send_notification also
assumed that send was the correct method, this should be changed
accordingly

Change-Id: I9406d74f3dc13c44d1aaad5379aafbf1a8580137

commit_message:
Utilizes assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone - tests/virt

Using assertTrue and the 'is None' operator to test if an element is None
is too python2.4. Our unit testing framework 'testtools' supports
assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone, included from python 2.7,
which were created for these types of tests.

Change-Id: Iee1379b941f93388900e89388676000b845fc8fc

commit_message:
Replace assertEquals with assertEqual - tests/api

The method assertEquals has been deprecated since python 2.7.
http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases

Also in Python 3, a deprecated warning is raised when using assertEquals
therefore we should use assertEqual instead.

This is part of blueprint assertequal

Change-Id: I72f612cc62f90a079c9c53747e3bcbfebfb8eb96

commit_message:
Make unshelve use new style BDM

Unshelving an instance requires recreating it, and since change
I5b9c3e2d959c602fa22f49db681da918ae0adcea, it is necessary to call
compute manager's _prep_block_device with new style BDMs.

This patch makes the conductor return new-style BDMs when unshelving the
instance.

Closes-bug: 1246412
blueprint: clean-up-legacy-block-device-mapping

Change-Id: I0ba9f53c31c4d5238319cfd09600ad64f298629e

commit_message:
Make non-admin users can unshelve a server

If non-admin users try to unshelve a server, nova-compute fails due to
"User does not have admin privileges" while getting hypervisor_hostname.
This patch changes the user context to admin's one temporarily to get the
hypervisor_hostname.

Closes-Bug: 1245312
Change-Id: I84dce1f7694d09c1281da13c6008bb3aa5940f85

commit_message:
Ensure clients get tested correctly in upgrades

Client libraries don't have branches, so when a change comes in
from python-novaclient the ZUUL_BRANCH is always master. That means
we need to actually check to see if ZUUL_BRANCH is BRANCH, not
base_branch, which is what we were passed by setup_workspace.

Change-Id: I6c7811b279d3450400bb5be140851dbfb52dbc16

Add support for oozie in HDP plugin

contains the OOZIE_SERVER and OOZIE_CLIENT host components

Implements blueprint hdp-oozie-support

commit_message:
Restrict the pbr version

pbr version 0.5.22 has a bug when installing on ubuntu 12.04. This bug
is causing heat-cfntools to fail installation when pulling down it's
pbr dependency:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/python-pbr/+bug/1245676
Restrict the required pbr version to be 0.5.20 <= x < 0.5.22

Closes-bug: #1245684

Change-Id: Ifb0332489be2ff6ee2f84c28ae2f43f77ba77379

commit_message:
Use elevated context in resource_tracker.instance_claim

There's no requirement that the resource tracker be used by an admin
context, but the db updates for compute nodes won't work without an
admin context.

This updates instance_claim to match how resize_claim,
abort_instance_claim, drop_resize_claim, and update_usage function.

Needed by bp remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance

Change-Id: Ib5b11ee6009f910966fbb849f020eb86c55de319

commit_message:
Add updates and notifications to build_and_run_instance

Adds instance updates and notifications to match the updates coming from
run_instance()

This is one part of a series of patches to build up the
build_and_run_instance method.

Part of bp remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance

Change-Id: I8807fc15be54eaf93ecbfcc12382cfa5fcddc81f

commit_message:
Add network handling to build_and_run_instance

Allocates requested_networks and returns network_info to pass on the
virt driver spawn method so that networks can be set up on the instance.
If there's a failure during the instance creation the network will be
deallocated.

A failure to allocate requested_networks will abort the build because
the instance can't be built as desired.  And rescheduling to another
host is not likely to increase the chance of success.

This is one part of a series of patches to build up the
build_and_run_instance method.

Part of bp remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance

Change-Id: I83e562845f07a76fa3365d46f1bb4a44dbda6bc1

commit_message:
Sync fixtures from oslo and use LockFixture

This commit adds fixture to openstack-common.conf to sync fixtures
from oslo. This patch also updates the location from which
LockFixture is used. It was originally in
tempest.openstack.common.lockutils but it was moved to the fixture
module.

Change-Id: Icffa613b92e059926b5394e9881ae0d8fe7fa910

commit_message:
Stop auto-detecting glance API versions

This commit switches the image api tests from auto detecting which
api versions are available to having them explicitly set in the config
file. This is to make it explicit which tests are expected to be run
instead of assuming that everything is expected to work.

Partially Implements: blueprint config-cleanup

Change-Id: Ie958a7fb03ff502c5ea1783eaae9debb442c34ea

commit_message:
Reorganize project feature config options

This commit reorganizes the config options for each project into
separate groups. This makes it easier to identify where to set
which features are enabled.

Partially Implements: blueprint config-cleanup

Change-Id: Idf8c65ef9bbc11cadea236f0b1a491a0f82bb84b

[{'created': '2013-10-10 18:07:10.000000000', 'message': "feat: integrate shard storage with transport

This patch refines the interface and storage implementation defined in
the last patch and integrates it with the transport layer.

A few updates have been made:
- 'name' -> 'href' for listing shards
- limiting, markers, and detailed are all used
- use of common_utils.fields to clean up shards transport PATCH
- add missing init for schemas
- fix schema issues found: 'location' -> 'uri', __init__.py

The transports test base was updated to expose both the admin and the
public APIs. To accomplish this, the before_hooks are exposed as a
property, and the routes are added manually based on driver.bridges,
and finally, the app is wrapped the auth strategy if auth is
enabled. This allows existing tests to run as before, but opens up
doors for tests that need access to both the admin and public APIs.

A test suite has been added that exercises the functionality from the
transport side of the shard registry resource.

Change-Id: I5b8cdb3a11d29422762b52f1e15e33167eecb867

"}, {'created': '2013-10-22 22:05:56.000000000', 'message': "feat: integrate shard storage with transport

This patch refines the interface and storage implementation defined in
the last patch and integrates it with the transport layer.

A few updates have been made:
- 'name' -> 'href' for listing shards
- limiting, markers, and detailed are all used
- use of common_utils.fields to clean up shards transport PATCH
- add missing init for schemas
- fix schema issues found: 'location' -> 'uri', __init__.py

Larger change: the admin API concept has been expanded to include
storage. Furthermore, an admin interface contains the functionality
from the public interface *in addition* to admin functionality. This
applies both at the transport layer and the storage layer. Part of the
rationale behind this is to simplify unit testing. The other part of
this is that an admin should be able to do everything a normal user
can do in addition to their special functions.

A test suite has been added that exercises the functionality from the
transport side of the shard registry resource.

Finally, the way the FaultyStorage driver tests were handled was
changed. Something about the setattr magic in that suite's setup made
it such that *all* tests would use the Faulty storage driver. This is
possibly related to the use of lazy_property decorators. To address
this issue, this patch promotes the faulty storage driver to setup.cfg
visibility and removes the setattrs.

Change-Id: I5b8cdb3a11d29422762b52f1e15e33167eecb867
Partitally-implements: blueprint storage-sharding

commit_message:
feat: integrate shard storage with transport

This patch refines the interface and storage implementation defined in
the last patch and integrates it with the transport layer.

A few updates have been made:
- 'name' -> 'href' for listing shards
- limiting, markers, and detailed are all used
- use of common_utils.fields to clean up shards transport PATCH
- add missing init for schemas
- fix schema issues found: 'location' -> 'uri', __init__.py
- shard resource correctly implements PUT semantics (replaces)

Transport: the admin API concept has been expanded to include
functionality from the public interface *in addition* to admin
functionality. Part of the rationale behind this is to simplify unit
testing. The other part of this is that an admin should be able to do
everything a normal user can do in addition to their special
functions.

Storage: now divided into control and data plane. The bootstrap passes
a control driver down to the transport which *can* be used for
endpoints as needed.

A test suite has been added that exercises the functionality from the
transport side of the shard registry resource.

Finally, the way the FaultyStorage driver tests were handled was
changed. Something about the setattr magic in that suite's setup made
it such that *all* tests would use the Faulty storage driver. This is
possibly related to the use of lazy_property decorators. To address
this issue, this patch promotes the faulty storage driver to setup.cfg
visibility and removes the setattrs.

Change-Id: I5b8cdb3a11d29422762b52f1e15e33167eecb867
Partitally-implements: blueprint storage-sharding
Partially-Closes: 1241686
Closes-Bug: 1243898
