With Docker 0.7 coming soon, I'd recommend to stay on 0.6.x and test each new version before upgrading.

Once Docker gets more stable, we can remove the version and just install "lxc-docker" which will get the latest version everytime. The nova driver hardcodes the API version so it will not break.'}, {'account_id': 7838, 'date': '2013-10-24 19:26:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7838, 'date': '2013-10-24 19:27:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7838, 'date': '2013-10-24 19:29:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I finally removed the version dependency for 2 reasons:

1. The API version is hardcoded in the docker client, so we're already safe on this side (when a new version is released)

2. Everytime a new version of Docker, forcing the package version on lxc-docker won't work anyway. At least with this change, devstack will be install to always install a proper docker."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-24 20:32:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

Can you work with #openstack-infra on that?"}, {'account_id': 2394, 'date': '2013-10-08 23:42:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I can't without some help on https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1235626 from Dean or someone else who knows how the website is generated.  I guess I can find someone on #openstack-infra for this, but it's unlikely to happen this week - next week at the earliest.

I'm not sure I understand the reason why work on the gate should block merging this, however?  Even if we extend the gate to check for shocco errors, we'll need them fixed before the gate changes, otherwise the gate changes won't pass the gate itself."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-11 20:30:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

I think I left my comment on a style checker in the wrong review...it would be great to have but I'd like to get these cleanups in before cutting stable/havana.

Adam, I'm the sole custodian of the build process for devstack.org.  That needs to change but it's been a low priority for me.  I'm using a shocco fork in my github: https://github.com/dtroyer/shocco/tree/rst_support.  Changes to the site itself should be done as pull requests to github.com:cloudbuilders/devstack.git gh-pages branch."}, {'account_id': 2394, 'date': '2013-10-12 11:52:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Oops sorry, I already replied in the other review - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/49847/

I said that it looks like there are already at least two utilities out there which could do the job:

http://www.shellcheck.net/about.html

https://github.com/duggan/shlint

so I don't think that building a new wheel from scratch makes sense here.

Regarding the build process, if you look at https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1235626 you'll see I already found your rst_support branch, but that still isn't enough information.  Please can you attach to that bug the exact scripts / processes you use to build the website?  The bus factor should be increased from 1 ASAP ;-)"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-16 22:13:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I've worked over my docs script into releaseable form and proposed it in https://review.openstack.org/52226.  It is a first cut but handles all of the shocco processing for devstack.org.  It should be enough for you to duplicate what I'm doing if you run it with no args.  It'll create a devstack-docs-* directory inside based on the github master.  The major thing lacking yet besides spit-n-polish is the ability to push back to the cloudbuilders repo."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-24 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

"}, {'created': '2013-10-25 16:02:32.000000000', 'message': "zsh openrc compatibility

Replacing $BASH_SOURCE with ${BASH_SOURCE:-$0} makes devstack zsh friendly: in
bash, $BASH_SOURCE is used per usual; in zsh, where $BASH_SOURCE isn't
defined, $0 is used, which, unlike in bash, evaluates to the current
source file.

"}]
commit_message:
zsh openrc compatibility

Replacing $BASH_SOURCE with ${BASH_SOURCE:-$0} makes devstack zsh friendly: in
bash, $BASH_SOURCE is used per usual; in zsh, where $BASH_SOURCE isn't
defined, $0 is used, which, unlike in bash, evaluates to the current
source file.

Now you can source devstack's openrc from a zsh shell.

Tested with bash and zsh from directories other than the root devstack
directory.

Change-Id: Iab1a817b15d86144163b5094bb58f94b15c598a0

commit_message:
Ensure cm-api is ready before start cm-alarm

The patch ensure that ceilometer-api is ready before
starting the ceilometer-alarm-evaluator service.

This ensure that ceilometer-alarm-evaluator doesn't log a error message
on startup due to not yet available ceilometer-api.

Closes bug: #1243249

Change-Id: Icff3e972ec485f26c014071f68079593a14b7240

[{'created': '2013-10-28 18:21:49.000000000', 'message': "xenapi: always reset JeOS's network

If the JeOS template contained an exotic network configuration, the VM

commit_message:
xenapi: always reset JeOS's network

If the JeOS template contained an exotic network configuration, the VM
prep step might fail. This patch resets the networking of the VM before
starting it.

Fixes bug 1245607

Change-Id: I921f1fdd0709d7a7760c4bb165e32f3898098bff

commit_message:
Allow configure cinder with the nfs driver

This patch allow to use nfs as cinder driver.

To use it, in the localrc we can now set

CINDER_DRIVER=nfs
CINDER_NFS_SERVERPATH=172.16.0.50:/export_cinder

The nfs-server is not setup by devstack.

Change-Id: I8e240d00b58f272d04ab2c0922c551b1f7266260

Updates InstanceMetadata so that it passes an instance
object instead of a dict to SecurityGroupList.get_by_instance
(which expects an object).

This fixes an AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'uuid'
error that would occur with the previous code.

This should fix a regression in
265431666ac3c4b65bf74e40c170d0d62eafe242 which landed earlier today
and broke SmokeStack/Torpedo.

Change-Id: Idfb75ee624789118e649faa414b84f0f5c4946a4
Closes-bug: #1246480
"}]
commit_message:
Update metadata/base to pass inst_obj to secgroup

Updates InstanceMetadata so that it passes an instance
object instead of a dict to SecurityGroupList.get_by_instance
(which expects an object).

This fixes an AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'uuid'
error that would occur with the previous code.

This should fix a regression in
265431666ac3c4b65bf74e40c170d0d62eafe242 which landed earlier today
and broke SmokeStack/Torpedo.

Change-Id: Idfb75ee624789118e649faa414b84f0f5c4946a4
Closes-bug: #1246480

The doc might be outdated.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-24 20:46:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

We already have SWIFT_EXTRAS_MIDDLEWARE_LAST, I think using SWIFT_EXTRAS_MIDDLEWARE_FIRST makes more sense."}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-10-25 11:57:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm the one who added SWIFT_EXTRAS_MIDDLEWARE_LAST, which is not the best name ever. SWIFT_EXTRAS_MIDDLEWARE_NO_AUTH looks like a very good name to me: it makes it quite clear that it should be used for middlewares that must be added to the pipeline before the authentication modules. I'd like to keep it that way."}, {'account_id': 7020, 'date': '2013-10-25 13:10:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

SWIFT_EXTRAS_MIDDLEWARE_FIRST would imply that the middleware is added at the beginning of the pipeline, which is not exactly what it's doing. SWIFT_EXTRAS_MIDDLEWARE_NO_AUTH would be included only before the first authentication middleware.

I don't think there's a major use case for inserting middlewares before catch-error and healthcheck. If there is, then we could create another variable SWIFT_*_FIRST then."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-25 15:02:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm not going to argue semantics, if you think that is the best name for its function, ok.  But you do use it to initialize $swift_pipeline and then only append to it, so functionally, it is the first user-configurable value even if it isn't the first value in the end pipeline.

The quote comment stands however."}, {'account_id': 7020, 'date': '2013-10-25 15:27:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-10-25 15:28:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I added the quotes.

commit_message:
Enables Swift crossdomain middleware by default

This step is needed to enable its testing in Tempest. The patch adds a
variable SWIFT_EXTRAS_MIDDLEWARE_NO_AUTH that holds a list of
middlewares inserted in the pipeline before authentication middlewares
(tempauth, keystoneauth, ...).

Change-Id: I1927103feff997a354ccf82ccf12aa77db083ad3

[{'created': '2013-10-29 18:45:21.000000000', 'message': 'Metadata port bug in L3 puppet manifest

This patch modifies the default metadata port that the
L3 agent redirects to if installed using the puppet
manifests. An inconsistency between the metadata service
listen port and the L3 redirection port causes clients
to be redirected to a non-existent service. This patch
ensures that the ports match.

Change-Id: Iea44fd42c6c5b2a6f25fb31b84b7ee140da9d059
'}]
commit_message:
Metadata port bug in L3 puppet manifest

This patch modifies the default metadata port that the
L3 agent redirects to if installed using the puppet
manifests. An inconsistency between the metadata service
listen port and the L3 redirection port causes clients
to be redirected to a non-existent service. This patch
ensures that the ports match.

Change-Id: Iea44fd42c6c5b2a6f25fb31b84b7ee140da9d059

'}, {'account_id': 2835, 'date': '2013-10-21 17:09:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

I'm not very familiar with this area of the code, but it seems odd to have _get_auth_token() doing auth and then also having the capability to auth within the v2.0 Client code path.  

You are adding the params to _get_client to support v2.0 Client doing the auth, so can we get rid of the first auth attempt then?"}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2013-10-22 12:35:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I tend to agree that we could simply delegate all of the token handling to the neutron client, since it will persist its state and handle re-authentication on its own.

Others have noted that it may cause a race condition of sorts because the client would be utilizing the same token for a majority of the requests.

There was another change set attempting to also handle the excessive token creation (which would be mitigated by allowing neutron to handle all of the token creations).  It is noted here:  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/50146/

The focus on this change set isn't so much fundamentally changing the way tokens are managed.  That is a broader discussion that can be seen in the other change.  The focus of this is how to stop a failure once the token expires."}, {'account_id': 2835, 'date': '2013-10-22 15:23:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Right, I wasn't suggesting making token handling more efficient, just pointing out that it looks like the v2.0 client will do auth anyway if a token isn't passed in:

https://github.com/openstack/python-neutronclient/blob/master/neutronclient/v2_0/client.py#L1151

In other words, the call to _get_auth_token() in nova/network/neutronv2/__init__ seems rather redunant, so I was just suggesting a minor cleanup."}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2013-10-22 18:26:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (3 inline comments)

Provided response comments.'}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2013-10-22 18:28:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Also, per previous comment.  Absolutely correct that the neutron client will try to re-authenticate if the token is expired.  The issue that this resolves is passing in the information to the client that it needs to perform the re-authentication properly.

Without the extra parameters passed in, the re-authentication fails.'}, {'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2013-10-22 18:36:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I agree with keeping the focus on this on expired tokens and handling that case better. I looked over this again.  The one thing that worries me right now is that it seems that with this patch, at any given time, we could be using either the user or an admin token for neutron calls.  It won't be consistent.

If you call get_client() with the regular user context (most cases), it uses the user token.  With this patch, when it re-authenticates, it will be an admin token, changing things.

I don't have a good answer for what to do about it right now, but that seems like a problem.

commit_message:
Pass thru credentials to allow re-authentication

Nova's network client obtains a token from keystone for authenitcation
to the neutron services.  When the timeout of keystone is set low, it
creates a condition where some of the invocations to neutron start
failing.

This is because the neutron client detects that the token is expired,
but during the re-authorization attempt fails due to not having enough
information to properly reauthorize.  Nova also assumes that within a
given context, the token will always be valid.  It does not perform the
authorization check (and doing so would be double verification as the
neutron client is already validating this).

Since the neutron client has logic in place to re-authorize the token,
this change set will pass thru the credentials to the neutron client
for the re-authorization attempts.  This change also updates the unit
tests.

Note: the change only will pass in the admin credential information
if the context indicates that it is an admin.

Change-Id: I2858562b180f3e058a2da9d67bef02af80927177
Closes-Bug: #1241275

commit_message:
xenapi: apply firewall rules in finish_migrate

When security groups were added, the rules were not re-applied to
servers that have been migrated to a new hypervisor.

This change ensures the firewall rules are applied as part of creating
the new VM in finish_migrate. This code follows a very similar pattern
to the code in spawn, and that is where the cut and paste code comes
from. This code duplication was removed in Havana.

Fixes bug 1073306

Change-Id: I6295a782df328a759e358fb82b76dd3f7bd4b39e

commit_message:
xenapi: enforce filters after live-migration

Currently and network filters, including security groups, are
lost after a server has been live-migrated.

This partially fixes the issue by ensuring that security groups are
re-applied to the VM once it reached the destination, and been started.

This leaves a small amount of time during the live-migrate where the VM
is not protected. There is a further bug raised to close the rest of
this whole, but this helps keep the VM protected for the majority of the
time.

Fixes bug 1202266

(Cherry picked from commit: 5cced7a6dd32d231c606e25dbf762d199bf9cca7)

Change-Id: I66bc7af1c6da74e18dce47180af0cb6020ba2c1a

to retrieve and delete its DHCP port, it does so by selecting
for update. This has been done by introducing a new method
that combine the get and delete in one shot: delete_ports by
filters.

commit_message:
Avoid dhcp agent race condition on subnet and network delete

This patch ensures that, when the dhcp agent queries the server
to retrieve and delete its DHCP port, it does so by selecting
for update. This has been done by introducing a new method
that combines the get and delete in one shot.

Closes-Bug:1197627

Change-Id: I1e8a87d7dc1a1cb9309aeefd41619e20f49f95a6

commit_message:
add property prefix filter support in image_list_detail

this add the property prefix filter support in image_list_detail
of the image service client.
so we submit request as the following to get specified images

GET /images/detail?property-backup_type=daily&property-image_type=backup

Change-Id: I8400bd4575165df2653c2b454ffc91517628ddbf

commit_message:
[PRD-1308] network range intersection check NovaNet

    1. Check intersection between networks address spaces
    2. Check intersection inside Public and Floating address spaces
    3. Check intersection of untagged networks on one interface

commit_message:
Adds api test to test_images

This adds a testcase to test api's
get image by id
get image file
also adds necessary client method for image client.

There was a confussion in the V2 imageclient function
get_image_metadata which has been renamed to get_image
to unify naming convention with V1. So there was change
made in test_images_tags.

Change-Id: Ie96135973b5796652e28aed2e3a09c17cfd26229

commit_message:
VMware: fix bug with booting from volumes

When booting from a volume without an image reference would cause
an exception.

Change-Id: Ib0302197b8d4f5e054a8c4426cb0dde7cb82842e
Closes-bug: #1235022
(cherry picked from commit 026843773b71ab0ac30abb36fe9eed92f5e11f7a)

commit_message:
replaces assertLessEqual with assertThat and testtools matcher.

Fixes bug 1233513.
assertLessEqual used in test_account_services is not supported by
python 2.7, so it is replaced by self.assertThat statement which
is compatible is python 2.6.

Change-Id: Ief6e062642d44f44fc924899d7cdd49154119287

Thank you for the patch. This looks good in overall. I will deep dive into this some more in the RC1 end.

I think there will be several fixes we should do before this lands in the end of RC1. Just what is in my mind now:

1. Extract the metadata of the meters to some class ( title, description, unit.. ), last time I checked, I couldn't retrieve it from the Ceilometer. So we should start defining it in the class by hard. It could be connected to Ceilometer and some cache server later.

2. Be able to define decorators for the meters for the statistics list, we can easily define that cpu should be decorated as 12.3days, instead of 1... ns

3. Maybe define default decorators, like always show GB instead of B. Though that default decorators could be redefined in the specific list.

4. Show the unit in the chart axis label

I will create bugs for this, we can set it as dependency for this BP"}, {'account_id': 7976, 'date': '2013-09-17 08:36:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-17 09:06:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Doesn't seem to work

Hi Maxime,

IMO there's far too much copy'n'paste going on here, duplicating similar code in the admin metering panel.

The problem is that fixes are already being proposed to the admin panel, for example:

  https://review.openstack.org/52868

is already landed on master, and the following are under review:

  https://review.openstack.org/53138
  https://review.openstack.org/53166

Unless you continually keep the duplicated code up-to-date, the admin and project versions of the metering panel with inevitably diverge.

So I'd suggest refactoring the admin code first to abstract out the re-usable elements. For example, openstack_dashboard.dashboards.admin.metering.tabs.GlobalStatsTab could be mainly (or entirely?) an abstract base class that both the admin and project panel use.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 7585, 'date': '2013-10-23 08:29:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add metering panel to project console

Some tables which displays informations about usage.
A linechart with choosable meters, and time
span.

Tests implemented over the resources retrieved tabs.

(fix: pep8 tests fail, commit message, translatable strings)

Implements: blueprint project-resource-usage-page

(2 inline comments)

Thanks for the patch.

A couple of minor clean-ups inline.

However, a couple of more fundamental issues also occurred to me:

- pagination is added to Meter*s*Controller here, when in practice there are likely to be only relatively few different meters to be returned, often sufficiently few to not require pagination at all. Whereas pagination support has not IIUC been added to the MeterController, when (depending on the query constraints) there are often going to to be many, many samples to be returned. Thus it seems to me that we'd be missing pagination in the very API (/v2/meters/<meter_name>) that is likely to need it most.

- I'm not sure about this idea of exposing multiple marker pairs in the API, while still requiring that a single marker object is *uniquely* identified. This seems likely to lead to user confusion when they inevitably hit the MultipleResultsFound exception as a result of too loosely specifying the marker. Is it a valid assumption that the marker will always be used to identify an item that the caller previously visited? (Usually the last item in the previous page of results). In that case, they should know everything about that marker item, specifically knowing enough to identify it *uniquely* via a single attribute (resource_Id, alarm_id, even message_id for meter samples). It would seem simpler and more consistent with the pagination approaches taken in other openstack APIs (nova, glance, ironic etc.) to simply expose a single marker param in the API and require that this is a unique identifier.

Just some food for thought ...

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 7642, 'date': '2013-08-09 06:51:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-09 06:58:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Works for me

@Fengqian.gao: LOL, looks like our two comments collided :)

On the first point, yes I think it would be fine to split off the pagination of the samples into a separate patch.

On the second point, IIUC the caller of the API must know currently that they are required to uniquely identify a single marker object. If the marker pairs that they specify don't fulfill this criterion, then the storage layer will fail the request with either a MultipleResultsFound or NoResultsFound exception, IIUC.

(I guess that could be made more friendly by catching those exceptions in the API layer and raising an appropriate BadRequest response with a reason string explaining that the marker pairs weren't specific enough to identify a single object).

So unless the caller knows quite a lot about what's in the DB, seems the only reliable strategy would be for them to always identify the marker object using a single PK-like attribute.

e.g. in certain circumstance I might know that only a single alarm associated with a certain tenant happens to have repeat_actions set to False, then I could use this knowledge to construct a set of marker pair. However, to absolutely safe, I would be better off always just specifying the alarm UUID as the marker object constraint.

So if that's the strategy that API callers are likely to learn that they need to adopt, would it make sense to require that in the API from the outset?

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2013-08-09 18:24:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: (1 inline comment)

commit_message:
Add pagination support to selected APIs

Provide API support for database pagination query. It supports
sqlalchemy and mongoDB with functions get_resources, get_meters,
get_alarms.
It is part of bp/paginate-db-search.

Implements blueprint paginate-db-search

Change-Id: I0f386e096ea5270e671d857797b8d4db521c478f

[{'created': '2013-10-08 15:44:47.000000000', 'message': "Fixes Hyper-V snapshot spawning issue

In Hyper-V, snapshoting an instance and then spawning a new
one using the resulted snapshot image with the same flavor,
will result an Hyper-V Exception.

Hyper-V will get the request to resize the base image to it's
actual size, leading to an error.

The reason is that the logic of the resize_vhd method has been
changed, as it is meant to resize images to the flavor size minus
the image metadata size, thus it's maximum internal size. For this
reason, the way to decide whether the root image should be resized
or not must also be changed.

So, instead of comparing the root image and base image sizes, we should
compare their maximum internal sizes.

Fixes bug: #1234759

Change-Id: Id16f905b7b1c82a1d322407fb52f3c1fd37582e6
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V snapshot spawning issue

In Hyper-V, snapshoting an instance and then spawning a new
one using the resulted snapshot image with the same flavor,
will result an Hyper-V Exception.

Hyper-V will get the request to resize the base image to it's
actual size, leading to an error.

The reason is that the logic of the resize_vhd method has been
changed, as it is meant to resize images to the flavor size minus
the image metadata size, thus it's maximum internal size. For this
reason, the way to decide whether the root image should be resized
or not must also be changed.

So, instead of comparing the root image and base image sizes, we should
compare their maximum internal sizes.

Fixes bug: #1234759

Change-Id: Id16f905b7b1c82a1d322407fb52f3c1fd37582e6

commit_message:
Allow multiple consoleauth servers

Send out the token updates on a fanout rather than direct exchange,
allowing multiple consoleauth servers running at the same time.

This breaks the previous assumption that when the call returns, the
consoleauth service has the token registered. But this also allows
to have a pair which will actually be able to respond when one of the
services dies.

Fixes bug 1243306

Change-Id: I3cc49dc9fb8c0404764d6e414611e084bbd2e171

'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-10-18 02:33:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

So I really like this idea, having client api testing is a cool addition. I would've liked to seen a blueprint on adding this testing before the submission, but whatever. Actually, I think you should make a blueprint for this and send an email on to the dev list with a qa tag to bring attention to this effort. (since I don't think it was on anyone's radar) There actually probably should be a summit session on this at HK because I don't remember client api testing really coming up before so having an in person discussion about it might be useful.

That being said there are a few structural changes up front that I think you should make here. You should break the base test class definitions out into a separate file. But, this also just raises other questions about how we structure things broadly (because if we add this for keystone we should add it for the other python clients) and it's relationship to the scenario tests. (an example, should we move the OfficialClientTest class somewhere more common if it's shared?)"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-10-18 09:06:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

>  I would've liked to seen a blueprint on adding this testing before the submission

Well these tests have been added at the request of ayoung, who said they were required in order to merge my keystoneclient patch:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48462/

So we've tracked adding them (specifically the trusts ones later in this patch series) under bug #1231483.  I can raise a blueprint too if you wish.

I do agree that adding client API testing in general (for all projects) will be valuable - Heat has a unique perspective on this, since we interact with all openstack services via their python client APIs.  If we can reduce the number of bugs and regressions we encounter by adding these tests I think it will be very worthwhile.

That said, I hope I can address your structure concerns and get this merged soon, so we get the coverage desired by ayoung in.  We can improve/add-to these "first-cut" over time, and I hope we don't need to gate these initial tests on summit discussions.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-10-18 14:25:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Do not merge

so I think we need to have a discussion about this before taking in client library testing, as that's never been in scope for tempest.

v3 API testing directly would be fine, and secondary testing by exercising the clients through interactions in scenarios is fine, but this is definitely a scope change, noted by this being a whole new directory structure, and not something to land without a mailing list thread or summit discussion."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-10-18 15:08:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-10-18 15:35:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tempest/+spec/keystoneclient-api'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-10-18 15:37:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

This was just a suggestion by dkranz, I can easily put it e.g under scenario/keystone if you prefer (that may actually be a better place for it, since this is not specific to the client, it's testing core keystone functionality, via the client.)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-18 16:10:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Doesn't seem to work

Splits paging config to max and default

Previously the max and default page size were the same value
for paginated resources. This change allows the max and default
to be configured separately.

Change-Id: I8798563729ed9aae3881393a57a6ab4a65f3e758

We haven't check the invalid attribute in a lot of extensions. For make v3 consistent, how about write some common code checking this. The parameters which update takes isn't actually extension specific so they won't be namespaced. Whether they are turned on or not is extension specific. commit_message:
Adds param check logic on v3 api server update method

This patch adds the necessary check logic on v3 server
update method to fix the issue which 200 ok is returned
even the param is missing or invalid.

Fixes bug #1213812

Change-Id: I167f4b5b2f6238fa78853ae1eff78d2c7e06b932

commit_message:
Use wsme ClientSideError to handle unicode string

We inherit from wsme.esc.ClientSideError to handle unicode string in
error message.

Fixes bug #1200518

Change-Id: I54a185a436b0a65bef13f303d7e31911cada76d8

@Darrell: with this change, there is no buffering behavior enabled, but raises the maximum buffer size provided to the sendto() system call.

The socket._fileobject.default_bufsize attribute is used to determine the maximum size of the buffer provided to the .sendall() method in sock._fileobject's .flush() method. So by raising it from its default of 8KB to our parameter default, we can be sure our larger buffers are not broken down into smaller chunks to send."}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2013-10-17 21:00:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Fine, how about this, then:

+    class myfileobject(socket._fileobject):
+        default_bufsize = 100000

+
+    class myprotocol(wsgi.HttpProtocol):
+        def setup(self):
+            sock = self.request  # actually the socket from accept()
+            self.connection = sock
+            self.rfile = myfileobject(sock._sock, 'rb', 90000)
+            self.wfile = myfileobject(sock._sock, 'wb', 90000)
+            # XXX this does not account for SSL
     try:
-        wsgi.server(sock, app, NullLogger(), custom_pool=pool)
+        wsgi.server(sock, app, NullLogger(),
+                    protocol=myprotocol, custom_pool=pool)
     except socket.error as err:

I tested this patch:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/48664/
Seems to work according to strace."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-18 05:11:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

As described in the commit message, changing the bufsize parameter to a socket._fileobject will cause it to not send until that configured size is accumulated, and then on the flush it will send it in max(bufsize, default_bufsize) chunks. So that in your example, it will buffer 90,000 bytes before sending any data (we want every set of bytes passed to the write() method written immediately). When it does write the accumulated buffer, it will dump all 90,000 bytes into the socket, but bufsize (90,000) is less than default_bufsize (100,000).

So when default_bufsize is < bufsize, then the writes will hang. So we can only change default_bufsize (until eventlet wsgi.py is fixed, see commit message).

We can make our own HttpProtocol as your patch shows, so I will try that out and see how it fares, reposting after I investigate.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-21 14:09:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Pete: are we sure we want to skip using the connection objects "makefile" method and use our class directly? If a special connection object is in use, we could be creating an object that does not work as expected, no?'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-21 14:10:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-21 15:10:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Doesn't seem to work

[{'created': '2013-10-15 16:37:38.000000000', 'message': 'Tie socket write buffer size to server parameters

By default, Python 2.*'s standard library "socket" module performs 8K
writes. For 10ge networks, with large MTUs (typically 9,000), this is
not optimal. We tie the default buffer size to the client_chunk_size
paramter for the proxy server, and to the network_chunk_size for the
object server.

Change-Id: I4dd93acc3376e9960fbdcdcae00c6d002e545894
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>
'}, {'created': '2013-10-17 07:44:41.000000000', 'message': 'Tie socket write buffer size to server parameters

By default, Python 2.*'s standard library "socket" module performs 8K
writes. For 10ge networks, with large MTUs (typically 9,000), this is
not optimal. We tie the default buffer size to the client_chunk_size
paramter for the proxy server, and to the network_chunk_size for the
object server.

One might be tempted to ask, isn't there a way to set this value on a
per-request basis? This author was unable to find a reference to the
_fileobject in the context of WSGI. By the time a request pass to a
WSGI object's __call__ method, the "wfile" attribute of the
req.environ['eventlet.input'] (Input) object has been set to None, and
the "rfile" attribute is the object wrapping the socket for reading,
not writing.

One might also be tempted to ask, why not just override the
wsgi.HttpProtocol's "wbufsize" class attribute instead? Until
eventlet/wsgi.py is fixed, we can't set wsgi.HttpProtocol.wbufsize to
anything but zero (the default, see Python's SocketServer.py,
StreamRequestHandler class), since Eventlet does not ensure the socket
_fileobject's flush() method is called after Eventlet invokes a
write() method on the same.  NOTE: wbufsize (a class attribute of
StreamRequestHandler originally, not to be confused with the standard
library's socket._fileobject._wbufsize class attribute) is used for
the bufsize parameter of the connection object's makefile() method. As
a result, the socket's _fileobject code uses that value to set both
_rbufsize and _wbufsize. While that would allow us to transmit in 64KB
chunks, it also means that write() and writeline() method calls on the
socket _fileobject are only transmitted once 64KB have been
accumulated, or a flush() is called.

As for performance improvement:

Run       8KB   64KB
  0     8.101  6.367
  1     7.892  6.216
  2     7.732  6.246
  3     7.594  6.229
  4     7.594  6.292
  5     7.555  6.230
  6     7.575  6.270
  7     7.528  6.278
  8     7.547  6.304
  9     7.550  6.313
Average 7.667  6.275  1.3923  18.16%

Run using the following after adjusting the test value for obj_len to
1 GB:

nosetests -v --nocapture --nologcapture \
test/unit/proxy/test_server.py:TestProxyObjectPerformance.test_GET_debug_large_file

Change-Id: I4dd93acc3376e9960fbdcdcae00c6d002e545894
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Tie socket write buffer size to server parameters

By default, Python 2.*'s standard library "socket" module performs 8K
writes. For 10ge networks, with large MTUs (typically 9,000), this is
not optimal. We tie the default buffer size to the client_chunk_size
paramter for the proxy server, and to the network_chunk_size for the
object server.

One might be tempted to ask, isn't there a way to set this value on a
per-request basis? This author was unable to find a reference to the
_fileobject in the context of WSGI. By the time a request pass to a
WSGI object's __call__ method, the "wfile" attribute of the
req.environ['eventlet.input'] (Input) object has been set to None, and
the "rfile" attribute is the object wrapping the socket for reading,
not writing.

One might also be tempted to ask, why not just override the
wsgi.HttpProtocol's "wbufsize" class attribute instead? Until
eventlet/wsgi.py is fixed, we can't set wsgi.HttpProtocol.wbufsize to
anything but zero (the default, see Python's SocketServer.py,
StreamRequestHandler class), since Eventlet does not ensure the socket
_fileobject's flush() method is called after Eventlet invokes a
write() method on the same.  NOTE: wbufsize (a class attribute of
StreamRequestHandler originally, not to be confused with the standard
library's socket._fileobject._wbufsize class attribute) is used for
the bufsize parameter of the connection object's makefile() method. As
a result, the socket's _fileobject code uses that value to set both
_rbufsize and _wbufsize. While that would allow us to transmit in 64KB
chunks, it also means that write() and writeline() method calls on the
socket _fileobject are only transmitted once 64KB have been
accumulated, or a flush() is called.

As for performance improvement:

Run       8KB   64KB
  0     8.101  6.367
  1     7.892  6.216
  2     7.732  6.246
  3     7.594  6.229
  4     7.594  6.292
  5     7.555  6.230
  6     7.575  6.270
  7     7.528  6.278
  8     7.547  6.304
  9     7.550  6.313
Average 7.667  6.275  1.3923  18.16%

Run using the following after adjusting the test value for obj_len to
1 GB:

nosetests -v --nocapture --nologcapture \
test/unit/proxy/test_server.py:TestProxyObjectPerformance.test_GET_debug_large_file

Change-Id: I4dd93acc3376e9960fbdcdcae00c6d002e545894
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

If a is was deleted at the same time as a role that the user has
been granted the server may respond with a 404 Not Found because the
user doesn't exist when the Keystone server checks for it.

Also, if the system is configured to use LDAP as the identity

while the role still exists. The role should be able to be deleted

of the user or group.

commit_message:
Allow delete user or group at same time as role

If a user was deleted at the same time as a role that the user has
been granted the server may respond with a 404 Not Found because the
user doesn't exist when the Keystone server checks for it.
Whether there's an error or not depends on timing.

Also, if the system is configured to use LDAP as the identity
backend, the user may be removed directly from the LDAP server
while the role still exists. The role should be able to be deleted
and not get a 404 Not Found.

(The description mentioned users, but this also applies to groups.)

The server is changed so that it doesn't check for the existence
of the user or group.

Related to bp use-common-oslo-db-code

Change-Id: If59a84a4f57d7be1d2639d0a2f0415e20292dfc3

'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-07-16 00:58:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think the checking for "not 304" is weird. There's already a way to tell swob not to do the range dance, and that's to set conditional_response=False.

It looks to me like the only thing that conditional_response controls in swob is whether or not to try to honor a range request. (WebOb did more stuff with it, which is why it's mentioned in so many places.) Further, it seems that the object server is correctly not setting conditional_response, so the proxy is getting a 304, and then the *proxy* sets conditional_response=True for some mysterious reason (probably WebOb legacy) and screws things up.

I tried removing the proxy's setting of conditional_response there, and it seems to work. In my tests with curl, I correctly get a 304 when sending the If-None-Match and Range headers. All unit and functional tests pass, too, except for the one this patch adds.

Here's a diff against your proposed change: http://paste.openstack.org/show/40491/

I tried out ranged GET requests against containers and accounts, and they work just as well as they did before (which is: they ignore the range header and respond with a 200).'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-23 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

commit_message:
Fix swob for handling request using Range header in conditional GET

When client requests conditional GET with range header,
proxy returns 416 response(Requested Range Not Satisfiable).
But it should returns 304 response.
This fixes it.

Change-Id: I24236f9f184714287f35054e9000ed2b68428dab
Fixes: bug #1196805

commit_message:
Remove instance_type* proxy methods from nova.db.api

There were several proxy methods left in nova.db.api to ease the rename
of instance_type to flavor with a note to remove them later.  This
patch does that removal and handles the impacts to the tests.

Part of blueprint flavor-instance-type-dedup

Change-Id: I2dd7a68ea028056996da6ea96a1fe3cae4ad0389

'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-05-13 21:33:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Haven't had a good chance to think this through yet, but I really want to avoid adding this config option

Could you describe the use cases for both the True/False values for this option?"}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-05-13 22:35:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The main problem I know of is when a user wants to drop in their own root logger and have all the logging redirected to the new handlers configured on that.

When fileConfig gets run currently with disable_existing_loggers set to True (the default), it will disable all the current top level loggers (apparently it doesn't disable the children loggers, determined by the package qualified name.) These top level ones no longer propagate messages to the root level logger since they are disabled, which is a problem. One would have to know all of the base level modules that were doing logging before the call to fileConfig.

I wouldn't have a problem with just setting disabled_existing_loggers to False instead of the config option. I would think it would be easier to filter out what you don't want with an external logging configuration rather than try to figure out what was there before and add it back in. Okay, getting very close.  Just a couple of minor comments inline.

I would like to see the help text tweaked.  Since that's user-facing it needs to be clear on what is happening.  I believe the way it reads right now is actually backwards - the config in log-config-append is appended to the existing log config, not the other way around.  I don't know if it makes a difference in practice, but I'd rather err on the side of caution and make it accurate.

I would also like to see the commit message cleaned up a little.  There's some old information in there that doesn't reflect the current state of this change.  For example, this is changing the behavior of log-config now, not eventually, and it's deprecating that option name in favor of log-config-append.  It would be good to mention that in the commit message.

commit_message:
allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig

Currently, common.log.py setup() will disable all existing
loggers that were set up before importing a custom logging
configuration from file. This patch deprecates option name
'log-config' in favor of 'log-config-append' and makes
disable_existing_loggers with default value False.

Closes-Bug: #1169328
Closes-Bug: #1238349
DocImpact

Change-Id: I1f25300d44b04ca5bcdd9b505319f0d089a9c964

commit_message:
Strengthen account tests

This fell out of Peter Portante's "acctcont-api" branch and seems
obviously good. Apparently one of these would've triggered while
doing the Pluggable Backend work.

Now, why commit this separately while simultaneously working on
a big unified Backend Patch? Because posting them separately
proves that the test changes worked on the old code.

Change-Id: I9ca6ad45fb255f5c0a177a93b93c1acc68da5bbe

commit_message:
Remove obsolete driver test module

Now that all drivers use the abc module to create abstract
base classes, there is no need to test that they raise
NotImplemented by default.

bp abstract-base-class-drivers

commit_message:
Documentation on how-to develop Keystone Extensions

This file documents in details how to develop an
extension following the Keystone guidelines.
It also improves the already existing `example` extension
adding some boilerplate code.

bug #1218596

Change-Id: I559aa219f8552c00d326c1b766078ff306e94bb9

commit_message:
Utilizes assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone - tests/etc

Using assertTrue and the 'is None' operator to test if an element is None
is too python2.4. Our unit testing framework 'testtools' supports
assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone, included from python 2.7,
which were created for these types of tests.

Change-Id: If3824356ddf4e6e2d91f6bc2fbfa41946d8463cc

commit_message:
NetApp unit test fail fix for http_proxy

The environment having http_proxy settings caused
the unit tests to fail with 404 error. This fix
handles both situations with proxy or without
proxy settings.

Change-Id: I791a45adff654305db9f1fb6f039e91b11ba88d8
Closes-Bug:#1223145

commit_message:
Allow spaces in quoted SSH command arguments

The check_ssh_injection() method was rejecting arguments with spaces
even when they were quoted, this was causing problems with some volume
driver commands such as commands for a storage pool with spaces in the
name.

Closes-Bug: #1244415
Change-Id: Ie4b809e1b39fdb752cf634e6d3c0a3924d8ac52b

commit_message:
Ensure keystone endpoint set before service starts

As neutron-server is mostly useless without having the keystone
service+endpoint set, in the case where both keystone and
neutron-server are on the same machine, this patch adds a soft
dependency to ensure that the keystone catalog includes neutron

This has a knock on effect of fixing openstack::provisioner, which
would sometimes try to create neutron networks, the type for which
soft depends on neutron-server, without there being an endpoint
set in the keystone catalog

Change-Id: I658e1b3e2c448b9a7da9e013c4e105b9ec824893

commit_message:
[WIP] Adds a new table TaskInfo

- move 'input', 'message' and 'result' columns to table 'task_info'
- introduce migration script for the above db changes.
- introduce new domain object SparseTask
- introduce 'run_at' column to the 'tasks' table
- introduce TaskRepo(proxy.Repo) and SparseTaskRepo(proxy.Repo).
- seperate out soft delete columns to 'SoftDeleteMixin' from 'ModelBase'
- introduce GlanceBase(SoftDeleteMixin, ModelBase). Have it extended by respective model entities.

partly implements bp async-glance-workers

Change-Id: Ia5d9d953ce1c9934277e96d11ad0d086699da164

If specifying non-dict data(string, etc.) as metadata, "create a vm"
API returns a HTTP500(Internal Server Error) response because it does
not validate the metadata type.

This patch adds the metadata type validation, and the API will return
a HTTP400(Bad Request) response.

Closes-Bug: 1238344

commit_message:
Add a metadata type validation when creating vm

If specifying non-dict data(string, etc.) as metadata, "create a vm"
API returns a HTTP500(Internal Server Error) response because it does
not validate the metadata type.

This patch adds the metadata type validation, and the API will return
a HTTP400(Bad Request) response. In addition, this patch removes log.WARNs
of bad incoming requests because they are just client-side problems not
server-side.

Closes-Bug: 1238344
Change-Id: I8f1d5debf74891e67b17f8128cc0eb0ab7f5c3f5

commit_message:
Print a more correct error with event-show

Just print out what the server sent us as the
error could be wrong:
- stack_name/id
- resource name
- event id

Change-Id: Ie48a549538a9809c8433b115537394a791d60147
Closes-bug: #1242947

commit_message:
Pin version of pbr in Cloud Server resource

This is a temporary workaround for a bug in pbr 0.5.22 which causes
the heat-cfntools install to fail.  More details at:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/python-pbr/+bug/1245676

Closes-Bug: #1245896

Change-Id: I9c0bc4d699af6782447efdd84bdde732664c8a27

commit_message:
Enable del of other tenants resources by name

Currently, due to the way that resources are being retrieved by the
findall() function, an administrator can do a list, snapshot-list, etc.
with the --all_tenants option and see other tenants' resources.  If the
admin then tries to delete the another tenants' resource by name, it fails
with a 'No <resource> with a name or ID of <name> exists.' error.

The solution to this is to change the call to the list() function in
findall() to set the all_tenants search option to 1.  This causes the
admin to get a list of all the resources that they have access to back
when the search is done instead of just a list of their resources.  The
delete by name is then possible.  The server takes care of ensuring that
only resources that the user has access to are returned.

This will enable delete by name for all resources that use the find_resource
function.

Closes-bug: 1241682
Change-Id: I4e9957b66c11b7e1081f066d189cedc5a3cb2a6c

Use abstract base class for oauth driver

Use the abc module for managing abstract base classes in the driver
layer.

bp abstract-base-class-drivers

Change-Id: I8c9b095ee012a4faca90ed026cea846b7d178dc2

commit_message:
HOT template to deploy servers in new neutron net

Add a HOT template to create a new neutron network and router to the public net
and to deploy two servers into the new network. Also assign floating IP from
public network to the two servers.
There is no special assumption on the image used for deployment since no
configuration inside the instance is done. The template is really just for
showing the base neutron configuration.

Change-Id: I8e177c3df3c82b37a163b13ee34b7c914b560479

[{'created': '2013-09-16 09:02:02.000000000', 'message': 'xenapi: fix race in get_all_vdis_in_sr

After getting the full list of VDIs in an SR, its possible that one of
the VDIs gets deleted.

Getting the record of a deleted VDI can lead to an HANDLE_INVALID
exception. This change ensures such errors are safely skipped when
returning the full list of vdi refs and recs.

Fixes bug 1225900
Change-Id: Ic69735e1a6caa893f63428141428ee0fd1a3ac65

commit_message:
xenapi: refactor get_all_vdis_in_sr

Making the code in vm_utils._get_all_vdis_in_sr more consistent with the
code in session.get_all_refs_and_recs.

Rather than catching all exceptions, the session.get_rec explicitly
catches the INVALID_HANDLE exception that xenapi might raise.

Change-Id: Ic69735e1a6caa893f63428141428ee0fd1a3ac65

commit_message:
Use abstract base class for token driver

Use the abc module for managing abstract base classes in the driver
layer and add missing methods to concrete classes.

bp abstract-base-class-drivers
fixes bug: 1227507

Change-Id: Ie8ebef10d1d0363813a07766433e18793fe448da

commit_message:
xenapi: strip base_mirror after live-migrate

There is a bug in XenServer CA-98606 that means you get base_mirror key
left over after a block live-migrate.

This change ensures to strip out that key after error live migrate, to
ensure the key is never left around in a way that means the next live
migrate would fail.

Fixes bug 1234752
Change-Id: Icd6ba17039b50ae20d252d7c052120abe7de0deb

commit_message:
Correct test for zuulifying the tree

The new zuulification of old requires that we know that we are on
the branch which corresponds to the old change. This means that
instead of having a flag to setup_workspace about whether we are
supposed to set it up, we instead need a check to ensure that it's
actually the ZUUL_BRANCH.

The previous attempt at this failed because the condition was too
nested because I didn't not fully understand the complexity of the
multilevel, multiply segmented, if condition that this was
attempted to be inserted into. By fully extracting it one level
this should be correct.

Change-Id: Ie787de3cb0b42b6b53b149dd528e0a20aae5c328

commit_message:
Fix wrong URLs in VPNaaS extension API

* GET /vpn/services/service-id -> GET /vpn/vpnservices/service-id
* /vpn/vpnservice/... -> /vpn/vpnservices/...
* /vpn/ipsec-site-connection -> /vpn/ipsec-site-connections

Closes-Bug: #1242751
Change-Id: Ifcdf3c2c7402210bfe8caabf4ad5c27d7c7b3f85

commit_message:
Make _get_instance_nw_info() use Instance object

This makes the _get_instance_nw_info() method use the Instance
object instead of a direct conductor query to do its job.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I53cc2e7844d5c4a43c6bb4c08c97f1547e5e6984

commit_message:
Convert evacuation code to use objects

This removes a couple of calls to conductor to fetch instances
during the evacuation recovery process.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I41c8ab3ecb85f5ecdca4d515a1d203296e9d5e30

commit_message:
Deprecate two security_group-related methods from conductor

The security_group_get_by_instance() and
security_group_rule_get_by_security_group methods are no longer needed
so this patch deprecates them here.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I43d01fc35b7e0989e96d053e980ebbf020264e37

commit_message:
Make metadata server use objects for Instance and Security Groups

This makes the metadata service fetch an Instance object to
do its work, and use the SecurityGroupList object to avoid
calling directly to conductor's API for those two things.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: Ia12f48227eb2380f5da93313cd4045577d8857c9

commit_message:
Pull system_metadata for notifications on instance.save()

When saving changes on an instance object a notification is sent out.
An attempt is made to pull flavor information from the instance but if
system_metadata is not joined then an exception is raised and the
notification fails.  This ensures that system_metadata is available for
those notifications.

Change-Id: Ifd317f847c3839cd6019038bb3dc856b9f107000
Closes-bug: 1244311

Fix all scripts to honor the enabled_ssl_apis flag

that start a WSGIService

commit_message:
Setting tunable[skip-name-resolve] to true

If tunable[skip-name-resolve] is set to false, hostname resolution
can cause auth issues.

Change-Id: I34b3b530786239c3c42ff1d8a44c536fea82f125

The node[openstack][*][rabbit] attributes for all the services using rabbitmq
(block-storage, compute, image, metering, network) should default to the same

'}]
commit_message:
ensure the node[openstack][mq] attributes push to the services that use rabbit

The node[openstack][*][rabbit] attributes for all the services using rabbitmq
(block-storage, compute, image, metering, network) should default to the same
values as node[openstack][mq].

Change-Id: I900f0eb0f7c5af00aa5995cd0a52845f00f1d813

commit_message:
Renamed "exceptions" module to "errors"

Changes exceptions.py into error.py

Renaming exception-related code to errors
because most of the conditions handled by
marconi are errorneous rather than exceptional.

Closes-Bug:#1232074

Change-Id: Ie3509236b07a372a44d97f97e5f3fe183b409606

commit_message:
Add container-sync functionality

This commit adds containter sync functionality by allowing
the cookbook operator to override the necessary parameters
to enable the feature.  It is backwards compatible, so unless
the attributes are overriden (and they have to be, only the
site operator knows the fqdn names of the other clusters) things
will behave as before.

It is presumed that different clusters are most likely controlled
by separate and distinct chef servers since they are more then
likely in separate geographical zones, so search functionality
here would be pointless.

Change-Id: I91b25946a2ce290e63492db5d5c3fae21ef05ce5

commit_message:
Refactor unit tests code for python3 compatability

The builtin basestring abstract type was removed in python3,
use str instead, we need to using six.string_types to replace
the basestring for py3 compatibility.

Partial Implements bp basestring-py3-compatible

Change-Id: I0f6a0f9ca4e17800407f3c1bbdce11a46288f693

commit_message:
Use packaged version of ordereddict

Removes the need for ordereddict source to exist in the project.
Uses collections.OrderedDict for python2.7 and above and falls
back to ordereddict.OrderedDict for python2.6

Fixes bug 1229569

Change-Id: Iaf8b500d7b340f370df239bfe9ab0656575dc93b

commit_message:
Add stats publishing support

* Various flags are available to enable or disable certain statistics
* Stats are published to a local statsd instance, where they can be
relayed to a graphite server so a large volume of stats can be collected
* A helper script exists which is run from cron to publish additional
statistics not built into swift statsd reporting like capacity details

Change-Id: I64bd50e270b3f9f41808c4a08f6f811400fb12bd

"}, {'created': '2013-10-09 14:05:15.000000000', 'message': "Implement queue's API methods

This patch implements methods for every queue operation. The 2
operations left out in this patch are: queue_list and queue_stats.

This patch makes the client, officially, usable as a library. An example
of how this could be use:

    client = Client()
    queue = client.queue('my_queue') # Creates the queue automatically
    queue.metadata() # Get's metadata from the queue
    queue.metadata(dict(new_meta='Yo yo!'))
    queue.delete()

Metadata was implemented as method instead of as a property to make it
explicit that both get and set do something in the remote server.

The client API was implemented in 2 separate levels. The highest level
is the one shown in the example above, which allows users to just query
Marconi instances without worrying about the transport, request build
process, references, deserealization and what not. The lowest instead,
allows the user to control every bit of the communication process - the
user can pick a specific transport, or pass custom params. For example -
which will make it possible to have other implementations around that
API in addition to the asynchronous support. Example of the API:

    transport = http.HttpTransport(cfg.CONF)
    request = request.prepare_request(cfg.CONF,
                                      endpoint='http://localhost:8888')
    core.queue_create(transport, request, 1, callback=my_callback)

There are tons of things to do and improve. For example:

    * The way config params are registered may work when using
    marconiclient as a library but they won't when using it as a CLI
    tool.
    * This code lacks of logging.
    * Handling of 20(1|4) is missing.

Partially-Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1

Change-Id: I8bdc8a4aff8ea22b5673bc7440e07796ecaf34cc

commit_message:
Implement queue's API methods

This patch implements methods for every queue operation. The 2
operations left out in this patch are: queue_list and queue_stats.

This patch makes the client, officially, usable as a library. An example
of how this could be use:

    client = Client()
    queue = client.queue('my_queue') # Creates the queue automatically
    queue.metadata() # Get's metadata from the queue
    queue.metadata(dict(new_meta='Yo yo!'))
    queue.delete()

Metadata was implemented as method instead of as a property to make it
explicit that both get and set do something in the remote server.

The client API was implemented in 2 separate levels. The highest level
is the one shown in the example above, which allows users to just query
Marconi instances without worrying about the transport, request build
process, references, deserealization and what not. The lowest instead,
allows the user to control every bit of the communication process - the
user can pick a specific transport, or pass custom params. For example -
which will make it possible to have other implementations around that
API in addition to the asynchronous support. Example of the API:

    transport = http.HttpTransport(cfg.CONF)
    request = request.prepare_request(cfg.CONF,
                                      endpoint='http://localhost:8888')
    core.queue_create(transport, request, 1, callback=my_callback)

There are tons of things to do and improve. For example:

    * The way config params are registered may work when using
    marconiclient as a library but they won't when using it as a CLI
    tool.
    * This code lacks of logging.
    * Handling of 20(1|4) is missing.

Partially-Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1
Implements blueprint queues-management

Change-Id: I8bdc8a4aff8ea22b5673bc7440e07796ecaf34cc

commit_message:
Benchmark scenario to boot server and bounce it N times

Implements a benchmark scenario which will boot a server and then
"bounce" it with specified operations: stop/start, soft reboot and hard
reboot.

A builder utility class is also provided which permits callers define,
bind, validate and build wrapper functions which encapsulate
calling an action method 1 or more times.

Partial implementation of blueprint benchmark-scenarios

Change-Id: I3cfba5c1ad1aff614027f52c13ebb63a420f4a2b

This fixes the get_nw_info_for_instance() method in nova/compute/utils.

If an instance object has no 'info_cache' (means we lack an entry in the
instance_info_caches table for the instance), don't try to access the
'network_info' attribute.  Just return a network model with empty
networking information like the dict version of an instance would do.

"}]
commit_message:
Fix getting nwinfo for Instance obj

This fixes the get_nw_info_for_instance() method in nova/compute/utils.

If an instance object has no 'info_cache' (means we lack an entry in the
instance_info_caches table for the instance), don't try to access the
'network_info' attribute.  Just return a network model with empty
networking information like the dict version of an instance would do.

Change-Id: Ib1f49f10cefeefc55a87fea69b6fbc772c978dca
Closes-bug: 1243291
(cherry picked from commit a907c2f06b65dca7c2c0ea6119fe649864c6de11)

commit_message:
ceph::repo integration tests

ceph::repo supports cuttlefish + dumpling on debian. Checking that
apt-cache policy returns the correct version shows the key was properly
installed and matches the repository. Omitting the release parameter
also checks that the default is cuttlefish.

Closes-bug: #1245177

Change-Id: I01ea92798db5d6d74507f247d3e49a93d1f0fc19
Signed-off-by: Loic Dachary <loic@dachary.org>

subject: feat: add catalogue storage driver for queues

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-16 16:58:27.000000000', 'message': 'feat: add catalogue storage driver for queues

The upcoming sharding feature requires a catalogue storage driver very
similar to that used by the proxy. This patch ports the proxy
catalogue storage driver to the queues storage space and updates the
semantics accordingly. Specifically, the queues catalogue maintains a
mapping from project/queue to shard identifier.

Unit tests and helpers have been updated accordingly. The sqlite
portion of this is still to be done, and is reserved for a future
patch.

Furthermore, minor py3k updates were added: metaclass using
six.add_metaclass.

Change-Id: I380d028520e9a712064810a15e2c6576de67e485
Partially-implements: blueprint storage-sharding
'}, {'created': '2013-10-16 19:11:59.000000000', 'message': 'feat: add catalogue storage driver for queues

commit_message:
feat: add catalogue storage driver for queues

The upcoming sharding feature requires a catalogue storage driver very
similar to that used by the proxy. This patch ports the proxy
catalogue storage driver to the queues storage space and updates the
semantics accordingly. Specifically, the queues catalogue maintains a
mapping from project/queue to shard identifier.

Unit tests and helpers have been updated accordingly. The sqlite
portion of this is still to be done, and is reserved for a future
patch.

The faulty storage drivers has been given the appropriate
catalogue_controller impls.

Furthermore, minor py3k updates were added: metaclass using
six.add_metaclass.

Change-Id: I380d028520e9a712064810a15e2c6576de67e485
Partially-implements: blueprint storage-sharding
Closes-Bug: #1241686

commit_message:
Remove security_group-related methods from VirtAPI

This patch removes the no-longer-needed security_group-related
methods from VirtAPI.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects
Related to blueprint virt-objects

Change-Id: I0326f25754e7a13dfc18f207242052412189c743

commit_message:
Make virt/firewall use objects for Security Groups and Rules

This makes the virt/firewall module use SecurityGroup and
SecurityGroupRule objects instead of relying on virtapi and
conductor for these operations.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects
Related to blueprint virt-objects

Change-Id: I39cb9422cb15e6222f5009f64706f1528035f42d

(1 inline comment)

I think the original bug report is wrong. The example should not change POST to DELETE. If we do so, people will end up deleting their account (which may or not work, depending on which version or type of auth middleware they use). 

The clean up of text (your're, etc) is fine -- but if done, could also be done in Delete Container Metadata section.

Just asked John Dickinson: DELETE account is not described in the document because we don't want people to delete their own account!"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-10-17 16:21:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Heh, good point. I thought the request was about deleting the account, not about deleting some metadata.

While it's technically correct* that DELETE /v1/acc will delete any metadata on the account, it's probably not what the user really wants.

* the best kind of correct :)"}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-21 16:21:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-21 16:21:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Small fix for climate.api.utils

Add changes in climate.api.utils The bug occured because function excecution
wasn't stop after we log an error with abort_and_log func. Fix it with adding
return statement after abort_and_log.

Fixes LP bug #1246244

Change-Id: I7351758c10163c01ed55ffe6028dac63f9d70c69

commit_message:
xenapi: workaround for failing vbd detach

Sometimes xapi returns with an internal error during unplug_vbd. This
patch adds a workaround for XenServer 6.2 by inspecting the error
message, and retry the unplug.

In addition, this also ensures that sleep is no longer called after the
last retry before raising an exception.

Fixes bug 1217972
Change-Id: I7b86325714e38b00a2f51bbf083b5532a6c51fa9

commit_message:
Updated the test unit running information

The documentation for running a specific test on nova is out of date.
The documentations shows that the test should be run as:
   ./run_tests.sh test_libvirt:HostStateTestCase
But the right way to run is to do as follow:
   ./run_tests.sh test_libvirt.HostStateTestCase

Closes-bug: #1234192
Change-Id: I507b17880879f83b5bb4ac8cb89d73947e1a9b95

commit_message:
Use pipe between ceph backup diff export/import

We now use a piped transfer between the rbd export-diff
and import-diff for incremental backups/restores as
opposed to holding the entire diff in memory.

Change-Id: I33476d9b3934781413af5cd2867a11d825a5d78e
Fixes: bug 1244464

commit_message:
Add support for openstack-common::sysctl

There are a number of sysctl settings in the OpenStack documentation that are
not managed by the cookbooks. This approach will iterate over any attributes
added to the node['openstack']['sysctl'] hash and write them out to
/etc/sysctl.d/60-openstack.conf.

The README.md had the recipe description within the Libraries section, separated
into new Recipes section.

Change-Id: Ic32184b78a0bcf4c3e704c7dcd1e9d009b1d95c6

Wraps code samples and changes to markup after O'Reilly run

After looking at O'Reilly PDF, address formatting issues.

Here's their wrapping points:

Body (top-level code): 80

Notes/Warnings: 74

commit_message:
Fix nailgun code to pass flake8 tests

Command for flake tests:
  flake8 --exclude=__init__.py,welcome.py,docs,fuelmenu
  --ignore=H302,H802 --show-source --show-pep8 --count .
Implements: blueprint fix-flake8-in-nailgun-repo
Change-Id: Ieb482b2f096c0e8563e2dcd8f2f26e131e9bc716

commit_message:
Quick pass fixes for ops guide old folsom links

There were a number of links in the ops guide that went to old
folsom pages for doc references.

Many of these can now point to the configuration reference, or
havana docs safely.

Few minor fixes to the text and adding status labels after review.

As to when to merge this - your call reviewerinos :)

Change-Id: I8844dcd9e7eb21584167f59fec2ed44bd1164761

commit_message:
Removes NoModule from the base testcase

Only test_keystoneclient actually uses NoModule so there is no reason
for all testcases to inherit it's functionality.

Change-Id: I4415ef32e89bb82242bb6b1fba24a7f2c0dc67e1

commit_message:
feat: proxy API improvements

A few minor changes to make the proxy admin API more user-friendly:
- added Location header to PUT /v1/partitions/{partition}
- added Content-Location header to all GET|HEAD|PATCH requests
- added HEAD method for catalogue and partition resources

Unit test suite was updated to reflect these updates.

Change-Id: I1987da3ae60380fe32371bf620efeb1e2fa6d811

exc.HTTPBadRequest where exc is in webob.

commit_message:
Utilizes assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone - tests/api

Using assertTrue and the 'is None' operator to test if an element is None
is too python2.4. Our unit testing framework 'testtools' supports
assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone, included from python 2.7,
which were created for these types of tests.

Change-Id: I09f38e219931e0d7ad27f04861d1ebbc3b5e2c5f

commit_message:
Fix the default rpc policy value

Before, each time a service that use ceilometer.publisher.rpc start this
annoying message appear because the default value is not the correct.

WARNING ceilometer.publisher.rpc [-] Publishing policy is unknown (wait) force to default
WARNING ceilometer.publisher.rpc [-] Publishing policy is unknown (wait) force to default

This patch set the correct default (to default inteads of wait), and check in tests
that the expected logger method is called.

Fixes bug #1245965

Change-Id: I41b9461359c7b0b17eb8e9dad1772bafdc3554fc

commit_message:
python3: Use urlutils from oslo-incubator

Python3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions
to different modules. Six provides a consistent interface
to them through the fake six.moves module.

However, the urlparse, urllib2, etc modules have been combined
into one module which Six does not support so we do it via
py3kcompat.

Also remove py2.5 compat block since it is not tested
and not supported version of python for Openstack.

Change-Id: I4038ad03a72bc8ceadc829e68a97b548c533eb1c

David,
max_rows is used for tatal number of all tables we want to archive. max_archive_rows depends on Database 's capabilty .
how many parameters can be handled in one SQL statment. It can be set according to Database's capablity.A another meaningful word should be better instead of max_archive_row to describe maximum rows for one table in one SQL statment.
Every Database has different limit for that.In another word the value can be known according to Database. This is different from the max_rows user want to archive.

This patch addressed Kevin's comment about circular import.

@Kevin,
There are unit test for this function see https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/tests/db/test_db_api.py#L6039
The bug was invoked by method of constructing SQL statement,and only occurred when there are large rows to delete.
For details ,please see bug description. Different databases have different limit of maximum total length variables,
so it's hard to write code to prove it . and That's not efficient ,need insert lots of rows in test table.

commit_message:
Add DeleteFromSelect to avoid database's limit

nova-manage db archive_deleted_rows fails if max_rows is a large
number. Database has a limit of maximum sql variables in one SQL
statement. It is more efficient to insert(select) directly and then
delete(same select) without ever returning the selected rows back to
Python. This also can avoid database's limit.

Closes-Bug: #1214720

Change-Id: I29e3a5ce14c59dd2979e45e8d31fc3df04c70266

commit_message:
Fix the developer documentation of the alarm API

Add body parameter in PUT/POST alarm method.
Add boundary to the BoundedInt doc name.
Remove no more existing alarm_id in put/get_one wsexpose method.
Use state wsme enum instead of unicode string for alarm state get/put
even wsme validation won't work to have the documentation generated
correctly.

Update sphinxcontrib-pecanwsme to generate the documentation of get, put
and custom pecan method.

Change-Id: I9587f3d640cc768a3d788542d2af138411dcee60

commit_message:
Allow Events without traits to be returned

Due to the join with Traits done in the SqlAlchemy implementation
of get_events, only Events with Traits can be returned from that
call. This would be expected behavior if Traits are provided in
the filter, but if no Traits are provided, all matching Events
should be returned. Even those without Traits.

The solution to this is to pre-populate the dictionary of Event
models before populating their Traits in the case of no Trait
filters being provided.

Change-Id: I4b0a5c20952f1dd5f2e2db631ffe1a14bd168fb3
Closes-Bug: #1245992

commit_message:
enable sql metadata query

explode metadata key/values to their own tables/rows (based on type).
build a key string using dot notation similar to other nosql db
and filter based on that.

Blueprint: sqlalchemy-metadata-query
Related-Bug: #1093625

Change-Id: I2076e67b79448f98124a57b62b5bfed7aa8ae2ad

commit_message:
Add ephemeral_mb record to bm_nodes

As the first step in making  baremetal support ephemeral partitions the
baremetal db needs to keep track of the ephemeral disk size.

Change-Id: I990f02a37799f4d9a3bde39a6058641a4a5314a4
Partial-Bug: #1238311

The module encryptors was creating a volume API instance in the module
scope which caused all the modules importing it to depend on
cinderclient.

This was affecting scheduler and cert services which at some point import
the compute manager module only to access their config options. It makes
no sense to force scheduler and cert services to require cinderclient.

commit_message:
Pass volume_api to get_encryption_metadata

The module encryptors was creating a volume API instance in the module
scope which caused all the modules importing it to depend on
cinderclient.

This was affecting scheduler and cert services which at some point import
the compute manager module only to access their config options. It makes
no sense to force scheduler and cert services to require cinderclient.

This patch makes the callers of get_encryption_metadata to pass the
volume api object to this method to prevent this dependency.

Closes-Bug: #1246103
Change-Id: I9eb4ae3754fa2a5ac646560a62477d6ed672e272

commit_message:
Delete objects completely

The soft deletion of objects in data store is not suitable for the
benchmark. The testing results became irrelevant after removal.

The rally.db.api.task_list ceases to support the active parameter.

Implements: blueprint rally-hard-delete

Change-Id: Ia9477423cebd26499e968f923961ee0f29685d8a

commit_message:
Add nova.db.migration.db_initial_version()

Updates Nova to use a new function called db_initial_version()
instead of the INIT_VERSION constant. This allows us to
move the top level INIT_VERSION = 132 into the
sqlalchemy migration.py implementation where it belongs.

Also, includes changes to do the same for the Nova
baremetal migrations.

Change-Id: I10dacdebb50d3121e3bfd094e40138807233aa64

commit_message:
Limit WSME to working version

WSME >= 0.5b6 breaks Ceilometer as it has been released in Havana. So
let's keep WSME with a correct version range.

Change-Id: I6974dd5562fb62354f8e7ae73f9f09881c7b88fb
Partial-Bug: #1240741

commit_message:
Update generate_sample.sh to allow custom configs

If any *.conf.sample files exist in the tools/config/
directory we append those to the generated script as well.

This allows projects to append custom config file snippets to
the generated config file and is useful for things like
keystone_authtoken information.

Change-Id: I2af0db4d5c47fc307540cdb0d1cce171d3aa5b27

commit_message:
Don't use sqlachemy Metadata as global var

In up>down>up mode migrations are failing due to using of common MetaData.
It should be declared separatly for both of migration methods.

Change-Id: I594c649def9a269033463558ba2aa9313f817ee5
Related-Bug: #1240898

commit_message:
Ceilometer UnicodeEncodeError when update or show alarm fix

Fix display bug in
ceilometer alarm-update
ceilometer alarm-show
when encounter a alarm with not unicode attributes.

Change-Id: I0af0f1d6b8393c7117eb5b56fba3d5e1f4935ff1
Closes-bug: #1245317

commit_message:
Limit WSME to working version

WSME >= 0.5b6 breaks Ceilometer as it has been released in Havana. So
let's keep WSME with a correct version range.

Fixes-Bug: #1240741

Change-Id: Iac8dfa6a7f5506423f467a96ed9ad0c70cbb35c5

exercices: aggregates needs to be more flexible

The actual regex checks a result in python format and
because of the change in the bug 1132961, Jekins failed.

I have update the regex to work with the old result
and the new result.

commit_message:
VMware: Using auto-gen table in cinder driver doc

Currently, the configuration options for VMware VMDK drivers are
hard-coded in the reference source xml (doc/config-reference/
block-storage/drivers/vmware-vmdk-driver.xml). This change replaces
the hard-coded configuration options with a reference to auto-generated
config options file at doc/common/tables/cinder-vmware.xml.

Closes-Bug: #1245784
backport: havana
Change-Id: I4efb85ef0d1e082eac77daa1722b6bab831ae67d
(cherry picked from commit 1e8460409f3cdb769cb321b45b6a76eb7c6121bf)
