'}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2013-07-31 06:37:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

What happens to the old stats data? This appears to discard it on the migrate which isn't ideal.

If the scheduler is making decisions off the stats then it will have to wait for all the compute nodes to report stats before it can do anything. This is a large downtime.

Using a JSON blob will also make it very difficult to do any queries for particular stats.

What did you do your tests on in the bp to get such a time improvement. It seems to me that 200,000 rows of stats should be manageable."}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-07-31 06:45:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Joshua Hesketh

Hi Joshua,

Please take a look at the discussion thread about fanout approach and the current DB approach initiated by Boris http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-July/012247.html

Thanks.
--
Shane'}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2013-07-31 08:05:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: No score

Hi Shane,

Thanks for the link. I've skimmed over it and I'm not convinced by the approach. I think the issues I pointed out are still valid but perhaps I miss understand (hence, no-score).

I'm also unconvinced by the need to rebuild the stored states of the compute nodes if the scheduler goes down. I think this will block unnecessarily."}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2013-07-31 09:40:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Guys IMHO it is too late for such changes.

We should wait I cycle.'}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-07-31 11:29:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Boris Pavlovic

Why should we wait for Icehouse cycle? I don't understand. At least this patch can improve the DB performance of Havana release significantly, and there is no big change or impact on the current code."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-07-31 12:21:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This is super-awesome!!!

Would be good to see some write benchmarks with the text field too as Boris seemed concerned about them on the ML."}, {'account_id': 6938, 'date': '2013-07-31 12:23:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

Revise the code per comments.

PS: I am writing the code to do WRITE testing mentioned in ML. If Boris can share the test code, that would be great.'}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-08-02 03:34:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-02 03:37:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

joins aren't intrinsically bad; removing a join will make the main table wider, and json blobs are likely to be TOASTed on postgresql, which may well decrease performance there when doing queries that don't involve the stats data. Also this will make scheduling with stats aware stuff harder.

/why/ does it improve performance for you is I think the key question : whats the data size, what DB engine did you test with (including version) and do you have query stats to show it's actually not doing something stupid like separate lookups?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-02 04:22:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

So I still think it is too late to merge this change, because denormalization is pretty big change (even if there are only 100-200 lines of code). And now we are in middle of H-3."}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-08-02 09:00:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Boris Pavlovic

Those who object the patch like lifeless raised the concern about how to query stats, and how to make scheduling with stats aware stuff.

I think the patch is still using DB method so I believe the impact on the current code is not so big. For the concern he raised, we also can support querying stats with JSON, and the scheduler still can get the information of stats for its scheduling.

Comparing with the 16 seconds delay with 10K nodes the current code has, this patch is 'bang for the buck'.

For the fanout method, I have no idea to answer lifeless's question?

For the best method you mentioned, I think we also can go ahead to do more tests and make a decision at design summit."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-08-02 11:38:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thinking about this further - I'd say I probably agree that we should have a discussion on the summit regarding this before merging.

As for some of the comments above:

- I agree with lifeless that the irrational fear of joins is wrong and we should see what is happening on the query level.

- I also think that irrational fear of text blobs in the database that are never queried is also a thing. I personally think that given the problem at hand, this is not a terrible half solution that improves things for some cases apparently.

As for the whole discussions - I am mostly in the "databases are meant to scale" camp and think we should figure out how to deal with the data in certain deployments (cache, get only certain stuff etc.) and build tools around that, instead of looking for the mythical unicorn on a silver bullet to replace the database.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2013-08-02 11:46:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Removed compute_node_stats table to reduce join

The table compute_node_stats is used to save additional statistics information
of compute nodes. However, nova schedulers need to call compute_node_get_all()
to get node information, which causes performance drop by join when the number
of the nodes is huge.

This patch is to remove the table compute_node_stats and to save 'stats' into
compute_nodes to avoid join in compute_node_get_all().

This is for the blueprint db-compute-node-stats-remove.

Change-Id: Ic51e61bf3c3a8b05623ad23908c4c4a580253df6
Signed-off-by: Shane Wang <shane.wang@intel.com>

VMware: Added doc for VMware VMDK cinder driver

'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-08-01 19:14:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

You're going to a lot of effort to take normalized version numbers and convert them back to an actual version.  The problem is that it's driver dependent, but the scheduler doesn't know which driver is loaded.  A quick glance through the virt drivers indicates that only libvirt and xenapi convert their version number to something different, and only libvirt seems to use it that way.  I think the right approach would be to make sure the hypervisor_version that the compute sends to the scheduler is a version number that can be used for the image_props check.  Otherwise you need to come up with a normalization scheme that works for all version types."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-08-06 11:52:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I have a feeling this should be a separate filter, that would reduce some of these concerns. It could then be loaded only for drivers that support the given type of version numbers.

There are two inputs:
- image prop, implying certain support versions
- reported driver version

It seems odd to pick libvirt as the standard version type. Probably best to discuss what is the best version to use on the dev mailing list.

It would probably be better if we all picked a.b.c.d or (a,b,c,d) as the version type, where a,b,c,d are numbers. The comparison should work fine then, using the existing tools.

Also, if the driver and the image props used the same type of version number, it would make a lot more sense."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-14 06:03:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-14 06:03:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Abandoned

There was a discussion in the dev mailing list and we all agree on having the hypervisor_version as a string in 'a.b.c.d' format where a,b,c,d are numbers.

However the db filed in compute_nodes is an integer. There's a blueprint created to change it to a string. https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/save-hypervisor-version-as-string

This commit will not change the existing values, but converts it to a version string for comparison"}, {'account_id': 6992, 'date': '2013-08-28 05:02:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: (2 inline comments)

'}, {'created': '2013-07-18 13:20:27.000000000', 'message': 'Adding support for multiple hypervisor versions

This is to prevent instances with newer tools from being provisioned
on older hypervisors.
Added comparison of hypervisor version from the compute-node and image
metadata in the image properties filter.
In host scheduler image_prop_filter, the 'hypervisor_version_requires'
image properties, if available, is compared to the host_state's
hypervisor_version, if available.
hypervisor_version_requires should be added on the image as metadata and
should have a operator and version value.
Examples : ">=6.0", ">6.0, <6.2", ""!=6.1"

Partially Implements blueprint xen-support-for-hypervisor-versions
Cell scheduler changes coming up in another commit.

commit_message:
Adding support for multiple hypervisor versions

This is to prevent instances with newer tools from being provisioned
on older hypervisors.
Added comparison of hypervisor version from the compute-node and image
metadata in the image properties filter.
In host scheduler image_prop_filter, the 'hypervisor_version_requires'
image properties, if available, is compared to the host_state's
hypervisor_version, if available.
hypervisor_version_requires should be added on the image as metadata and
should have a operator and version value.
Examples : ">=6.0", ">6.0, <6.2", ""!=6.1"

Partially Implements blueprint xen-support-for-hypervisor-versions
Cell scheduler changes coming up in another commit.
DocImpact

Change-Id: I6fbf232adf9ac78ebb8ac2985739f163f4517d14

commit_message:
Replace tests.base part6

It is the sixth step to replace using ceilometer.tests.base with
openstack.common.test.
In this patch is changed for using
openstack.common.test and added needed fixtures in
test classes.
Added in ceilometer.tests.db code from ceilomete.tests.base
because ceilometer.tests.base will not be used in the future.

Change-Id: I3cacca4eff19eae8874decd892ab1225f95cfee9

commit_message:
Respect storage pool path in create-nodes script

The create-nodes script didn't cope well with libvirt storage pool
named "default" being in non-standard location. It created the images
in correct location, but passed incorrect image path into configure-vm
script, because the image path was hard coded.

Now the script queries for correct location of the image using virsh.

Change-Id: Ia049a7496d4df0ae9f0c606a3d6279b9f94c56fc

commit_message:
Allow Neutron to schedule networks lazily

When a new network is created, Neutron won't schedule it
to one of the active DHCP agents until the first port on
this network is allocated.

This means that we should not bother to schedule the created
network manually and can just rely on Neutron for doing this
(actually, we've already been relying on Neutron for Seed VM,
since we switched to using of neutron-dhcp-agent).

Related-Bug: #1231366

Change-Id: I413407effe93312f2b5dd69d673590043becca33

commit_message:
VMware: Using auto-gen table in cinder driver doc

Currently, the configuration options for VMware VMDK drivers are
hard-coded in the reference source xml (doc/config-reference/
block-storage/drivers/vmware-vmdk-driver.xml). This change replaces
the hard-coded configuration options with a reference to auto-generated
config options file at doc/common/tables/cinder-vmware.xml.

Closes-Bug: #1245784
backport: havana
Change-Id: I4efb85ef0d1e082eac77daa1722b6bab831ae67d

commit_message:
Reworks HTTP Patch support and adds validation for Node

Adds in reference implementation for:

Initial work for adding validation to WSME complex
types (this adds an initial layer of validation when
the data first enters the API)

Adding support for blacklisting of attributes.

Also, reworks much of the common HTTP Patch code into
resuable methods accessible in the WSME complex types.
Change-Id: I030b08a719c962f419f45e35e9d7a72e1eb0042f

commit_message:
improve perfomance of nailgun component

builtin json serialization is slow
use ujson library for parts where we have perfomance issues

Change-Id: Ia78186c27f61a8ef58649a7d2d12ec20f8c79b73

commit_message:
Rename heat_watch_server_url to watch_server_url

The other *_server_url parameters are not prefixed with heat_ and this
is already in the heat namespace.

Change-Id: I24effcfedccb7b69b4e4d022db6676da51083401

commit_message:
Rename heat_watch_server_url to watch_server_url

The Readme for heat-engine says it should be watch_server_url and
{{heat.watch_server_url}} is what is being used in heat.conf.

Change-Id: Ibcfec34c85901592c47eaf911aeb2eaa8049dfb7

commit_message:
Support extention floating-ip-bulk-list when use neutron

When use neutron, the extension floating-ip-bulk-list still use
nova db as query source, the result always return [].

    * Add get_floating_ips_all() for floating-ip-bulk-list
    * Add get_floating_ips_all_by_host() for option '--host'
    * Add unit test

Closes-Bug #1230089

Change-Id: Ie933328c98457828c54ad7c6bfc1d80a353a9865

commit_message:
Add security groups updating test for ports

Add new function test_update_port_with_security_groups() for testing
update ports with new created valid security groups.
Add new function test_update_port_with_nonexistent_security_groups()
for negative tests.

Change-Id: Iba96704d132b6f4461b041216817ff718b59db9e

commit_message:
Grant apache permissions on Ubuntu 13.10

Just like https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1167066 does:

  Starting with ubuntu 13.10 the horizon.conf has
    <Directory />
        AllowOverride none
        Require all denied
    </Directory>
  which requires you to explicitly permit access to web content
  directories in other <Directory> blocks

Fixes: Bug #1241574
Change-Id: I16d6657a276884309c874471ea5c7f44b63685d8

commit_message:
keystone : Add coverage of v2 client trust scoping

Adds coverage of re-scoping a v2 client to a trust, as described in
bug #1231483.  the tests will need to be skipped until the patch from
that bug gets merged into keystoneclient.

blueprint: keystoneclient-api
Change-Id: I41afcdcafe89aa35ff03fbc373ab83c495adce38
Partial-Bug: #1231483

subject: Add initial keystoneclient trusts tests

commit_message:
Add tests for SQLAlchemy Util's `modify_indexes`

In preparation for a bug fix to `modify_indexes`, this patch introduces
testing around the existing functionality.

Additional cleanups:

* Added support for SQLite (no indication why this was originally skipped and
  tests pass)
* Fixed Postgres case (it failed with duplicate column errors)
* Added `get_indexes` helper
* Added `get_foreign_keys` helper

Change-Id: I38dc4e260d6aea446438202f1f5146ad3aa1b6fc

[{'created': '2013-10-20 17:18:28.000000000', 'message': 'Handle unrecognized CLI response for Huawei driver

To avoid the risk of an infinite loop when T driver reading CLI result,
this patch adds a determination of unrecognized CLI response.

Change-Id: I5438b9a2d0f395f914d0aa4f97b5819e34ec31b4
'}]
commit_message:
Handle unrecognized CLI response for Huawei driver

To avoid the risk of an infinite loop when T driver reading CLI result,
this patch adds a determination of unrecognized CLI response.

Change-Id: I5438b9a2d0f395f914d0aa4f97b5819e34ec31b4

commit_message:
Don't attempt to zuulify the old tree

In the event that nothing else works, this change can be merged
to prevent us from attempting to zuulify the old tree at all. This
is known to work if the rest of the zuul changes don't.

Change-Id: Idffb05d4438fdf45eafc1a8e1b9e371b210e60d9

commit_message:
Ensure apt-get installs do not prompt user input

Set DEBIAN_FRONTEND to noninteractive and add dpkg options to ensure
apt-get installs do not prompt for input and cause the stack-create to
fail.

Closes-Bug: #1245899

Change-Id: I294783fb565b854143bc8a5d15834d8d88ad1a70

commit_message:
Register o-a-c managed files with use-ephemeral

We want to have elements directly making use of /mnt, but if they have
not yet migrated to this paradigm and an image is meant to use the
ephemeral drive for state, we can force the issue here.

Change-Id: I876f1f807f7b9888189ce9ce898a9d19091f85e1

commit_message:
Quarantine objects with busted metadata.

Before, if you encountered an object with corrupt or missing xattrs,
the object server would return a 500 on GET, and wouldn't quarantine
anything. Now the object server returns a 404 for that GET and the
corrupted file is quarantined, thus giving replication a chance to fix
it.

Change-Id: Ib1d7ab965391742c88fde3d83dc0b5afe85bada9

commit_message:
Install Guide: Fix service names for Ubuntu and openSUSE

For Ubuntu:
openvswitch->openvswitch-switch
neutron-openvswitch-agent->neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent
For openSUSE:
neutron-openvswitch-agent->openstack-neutron-openvswitch-agent

Change-Id: I8fa175b9a666a41818c1fc590fc34a9afbb91e32
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: 1246021

commit_message:
Only zuulify the tree if we are on the right branch

We need to be more careful in our selection of when we zuulify the
tree, because we now want to zuulify the "old" tree as well. But
only do that if the ZUUL_BRANCH matches the $branch we've told it
to setup the workspace for.

Change-Id: Ie0ef097949aa54cb720615df80ed3aba4c16cc30

concat::setup has been made a private class and can no longer be
included from modules outside concat itself.

concat::setup is already included by the concat define. Removing

commit_message:
Fix compatibility with latest puppetlabs-concat

concat::setup has been made a private class and can no longer be
included from modules outside concat itself.

concat::setup is already included by the concat define. Removing
its inclusion from puppet-swift classes shouldn't result in breakage
or loss of functionality.

Change-Id: I7566e09bd4e93aec719a495279cf92d8a898057e
Closes-bug: #1245936

Could someone expand on why this was reverted so it's documented where devs might see it?"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-10-29 00:12:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

sorry, we were racing to fix things this morning in #openstack-infra, and a better commit message didn't really come to pass.

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-infra/%23openstack-infra.2013-10-28.log starting at about 2013-10-28T11:49:38

The net of it, we don't do zuul magic on the "old" side of a grenade upgrade, so an incompatible python-novaclient change that changes the UI, can break the devstack exercises, which only get run on the old side of the changes (so we don't catch it when you propose the change, but everyone behind you is now broken, forever).

The fix for this system is wrapped up in - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/53940/ 

After that is in place, I'll try to revert the revert and see if we managed to catch the incompatibility.'}, {'account_id': 7882, 'date': '2013-10-29 04:22:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Let us gate grenade forward

This sets up all the grenade variables both needed to cover Havana
and Icehouse runs, but also to provide a new DEVSTACK_GATE_GRENADE_FORWARD
that let's us do a forward upgrade on a stable branch.

Also, get completely explicit on all the branches, to ensure that we
know what directions we are headed in.

Update setup_workspace to take local variables of branch name to try
to make the code a little clearer, and move all the setup_workspace to
the same point in the script.

Co-Authored-By: Mauro S. M. Rodrigues <maurosr@linux.vnet.ibm.com>
Change-Id: Iffcbd127c20780c5de6a16c41d1f0fd9f0d4d470

commit_message:
Support port-list by node_id

The API service exposes "GET /nodes/UUID/ports",
but the client library doesn't implement this.
It is needed by the Nova driver.

Change-Id: Id3bb9d7d8c46102f4cb63a3ee65306cc07afb812
Closes-Bug: #1239028

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-27 23:37:08.000000000', 'message': 'Add DiskReader class to diskfile

Move all .metadata access under DiskFile "open" in object-server

Raise DiskFileSizeInvalid when Content-Length does not match size

When get_obj_size raises a DiskFileSizeInvalid error it will automatically
quarantine the object.  This makes the quarantine method on the DiskReader
effectively private except when it's used explicitly by the auditor for
generic handling of unexpected DiskFileErrors.

Any attempt to iterate over an instance of DiskReader will ensure that the
obj_size has been validated against the Content-Length in the metadata.  The
object-server already did this, and it is now enforced in tests as well.

When closing a DiskReader, if the _obj_size has been set (either by an
explicit call to get_obj_size, or by iterating over the body) the close method
will always automatically attempt to verify and possibly quarantine the file.
Since a Content-Length mis-match would have been caught before iterating the
file this always automatic close verification will only effect the ETag
validation which is only performed when the entire body of the DiskReader is
consumed.  Setting a "verify_close" attribute on the reader instance will have
no effect.

Consolidate quarnatine call sites on DiskReader

Add keep_cache_size to DiskReader constructor so that the DiskReader class may
optionally keep smaller files in the page cache.
Remove keep_data_fp argument from DiskFile constructor

All access to the data_file fp for DiskFile is moved under the new "open"
method.  This reduces the surface area of the DiskFile abstraction and reduces
the exposure of the underlying implementation in the object-server.

Move all DiskFile artifact manipulation under DiskWriter

All write access to the underlying DiskFile artifacts has been moved to
DiskWriter.  DiskWriter will create .data, .meta, and .ts files as well as
delete them.  The public "unlinkold" DiskFile method has been moved to
DiskWriter and manages it's calling.

Expose public helper method "update_metadata" to replace put_metadata, and
re-factor "delete" to use DiskWriter directly and more efficiently.

New public "delete" method on DiskFile

Change-Id: I6b9ed674a557b229f8a754ad335f8dc9053f0218
'}]
commit_message:
Add DiskReader class to diskfile

Move all .metadata access under DiskFile "open" in object-server

Raise DiskFileSizeInvalid when Content-Length does not match size

When get_obj_size raises a DiskFileSizeInvalid error it will automatically
quarantine the object.  This makes the quarantine method on the DiskReader
effectively private except when it's used explicitly by the auditor for
generic handling of unexpected DiskFileErrors.

Any attempt to iterate over an instance of DiskReader will ensure that the
obj_size has been validated against the Content-Length in the metadata.  The
object-server already did this, and it is now enforced in tests as well.

When closing a DiskReader, if the _obj_size has been set (either by an
explicit call to get_obj_size, or by iterating over the body) the close method
will always automatically attempt to verify and possibly quarantine the file.
Since a Content-Length mis-match would have been caught before iterating the
file this always automatic close verification will only effect the ETag
validation which is only performed when the entire body of the DiskReader is
consumed.  Setting a "verify_close" attribute on the reader instance will have
no effect.

Consolidate quarnatine call sites on DiskReader

Add keep_cache_size to DiskReader constructor so that the DiskReader class may
optionally keep smaller files in the page cache.
Remove keep_data_fp argument from DiskFile constructor

All access to the data_file fp for DiskFile is moved under the new "open"
method.  This reduces the surface area of the DiskFile abstraction and reduces
the exposure of the underlying implementation in the object-server.

Move all DiskFile artifact manipulation under DiskWriter

All write access to the underlying DiskFile artifacts has been moved to
DiskWriter.  DiskWriter will create .data, .meta, and .ts files as well as
delete them.  The public "unlinkold" DiskFile method has been moved to
DiskWriter and manages it's calling.

Expose public helper method "update_metadata" to replace put_metadata, and
re-factor "delete" to use DiskWriter directly and more efficiently.

New public "delete" method on DiskFile

Change-Id: I6b9ed674a557b229f8a754ad335f8dc9053f0218

commit_message:
Update to cleanup command for adapter

Now cleaning of db is available trough command line interface via
ostfctl util. In order to clean db use "ostfctl cleandb --dbpath
db-connection-string". db-connection-string is optional flag and its
default is for ostf database.

Change-Id: I0e6161e5b1a4d892e4f092b7506ac2e08e1bc2f8

commit_message:
improve model validation

- add isset to check "real" attribute and not descriptor
- verify only id is set in shortform
- verify either resource or resourceId value is set, not both.

blueprint improve-validation
related-bug: #1242830

Change-Id: Ie9e3f26c5d30cd36e6013a1f0b77c8fe466cb3f7

commit_message:
Ignore H803 from Hacking.

H803 checks for a period in commit messages, something the community
clearly rejected as a sensible check: periods in commit messages
should neither be rejected or required.

The email thread on this issue is here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-June/010837.html

Change-Id: I754e10ca01b3e6f8c6482e1bcd4c2e2ca8c1cfc9

This lets you build swift packages that don't require pbr
to be installed at all. You would need pbr on the machine running
rpmbuild / debuild, but not on the machines that install the packages.

Unfortunately, this does not make swift able to be
installed via pip 0.3.1 on Lucid; you'll need to uninstall the system
python-pip package and install a new pip some other way. Given that
pip < 1.3 doesn't perform SSL certificate validation for pypi (trivial

Change-Id: Ia50a229c5ae4dd2158beeaa953619b5e8f987c55
"}]
commit_message:
Make pbr a build-time only dependency

This lets you build swift packages that don't require pbr
to be installed at all. You would need pbr on the machine running
rpmbuild / debuild, but not on the machines that install the packages.

Unfortunately, this does not make swift able to be
installed via pip 0.3.1 on Lucid; you'll need to uninstall the system
python-pip package and install a new pip some other way. Given that
pip < 1.3 doesn't perform SSL certificate validation for pypi (trivial
MITM attack, anyone?), you'd probably want to get a new pip anyway.

Change-Id: Ia50a229c5ae4dd2158beeaa953619b5e8f987c55

commit_message:
Fix tests to work with mysql+postgres concurrently

Optimise tests.db.test_migrations and tests.db.test_migration_utils for
concurrency and make opportunistic tests obey walk_style configurations.

Closes-Bug: 1207750

Change-Id: Idb30f144fb67aefc58749897d774103c3c0ec640

commit_message:
Claim IPv6 is unsupported if no interface with IPv6 configured

When IPv6 is supported by glibc but no interface
is configured to use ipv6 (because the ipv6 module
is not loaded), skip ipv6 related checks.

Change-Id: I15aaf3d01f0f51bdc0bd29f30728ca2ab8b5c30a

commit_message:
Revert "move single host setup activities to setup_host"

This reverts commit e0df323af67940d6e2951828d3a2289591ab9301.

This is necessary as the changes made in this change are not self test
able and they broke the gate. Revert for now giving us time to write a
proper fix.

commit_message:
Fix compatibility with latest puppetlabs-concat

concat::setup has been made a private class and can no longer be
included from modules outside concat itself.

concat::setup is already included by the concat define. Removing
its inclusion from puppet-swift classes shouldn't result in breakage
or loss of functionality.

Change-Id: I7566e09bd4e93aec719a495279cf92d8a898057e
Closes-bug: #1245936
(cherry picked from commit 23cc3616cea78b8431181af748a1827add18974f)

commit_message:
Make chef-roles configurable

Change the chef roles hard coded in the recipes and
templates into attributes which can be overriden by
the cookbook end-user.

commit_message:
add metadata-agent network role

...and the accompanied entries in role[os-network] and
infrastructure.yml.

It seems like this was forgotten in the earlier commit,
323843237c10e5a8ebf245bc23ff159f9fe311a5, at least the OVS plugin of
Neutron needs this agent.

Change-Id: I69c0543597624497c9a40e731e355b8f64d5b3fb

and vdb setup in setup_workspace instead of setup_host. These really

not be in setup_workspace.

Change-Id: I53853954f7712a04a205cd3e0b87ece3465e1e0b
'}]
commit_message:
move single host setup activities to setup_host

we previously were doing corrections to the host, like the hostname
and vdb setup in setup_workspace instead of setup_host. These really
should only be done once per setup environment, and thus should
not be in setup_workspace.

Change-Id: I53853954f7712a04a205cd3e0b87ece3465e1e0b

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-16 19:22:15.000000000', 'message': '(WIP) Disable compute when libvirt is unavailable

Disabling nova-compute on libvirt connectivty exceptions.

In addition, allowing update_available_resource, periodict task,
to disable and re-enable the service, when libvirt is connected again.

It is being done according to the success or failure
(with libvirt connectivity exception) of the driver.get_host_stats
method.

This is in order to avoid migrations or new instances to be scheduled
on, a disconnected from libvirt, compute node.

Fixes bug #1240670
Change-Id: Ib8d67838ceb73c5b1cdc9498c17b335e9e5bb6f3

commit_message:
Disable nova-compute on libvirt connectivity exceptions

The service will be disabled and re-enabled according to the success
or failure of establishing a connection to the libvirt service.

update_available_resources, periodic task, will probe the connection
even if the service is disabled.

This is in order to avoid migrations or new instances to be scheduled
on a disconnected from libvirt compute node.

Closes-Bug: #1240670
Change-Id: Ib8d67838ceb73c5b1cdc9498c17b335e9e5bb6f3

commit_message:
Sync global requirements with glance

Some tests in master are failing due to variation of behavior of iso8601 package
in versions 0.1.4 vs. v0.1.5 and above. This patch introduces a hack to get the
tests working however, we should soon fix them soon.

Change-Id: I125379f2e400f1b6270e9a2cda30ef2a8e1b3924

commit_message:
Fix bug in Security Group association to Instance

* Refactor of security groups to TaskManager left out an assignment that
  is required for the security_group to be attached to an intance.

fixes bug 1245767

Change-Id: I161d50b2ddb50dbf25eb67e10414425f098b9979

commit_message:
Continue reserving H6xx namespace for calling methods

H6xx is reserved for calling methods (see
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#calling-methods), so move
the three H6xx tests to more approrate locations.

H601=>H903
H602=>H234 since the issue is that python3 gives an explicit warning
H603=>H235 same reason as H234

Since only H601 has been released, this will have a minor impact

Change-Id: Ie68c9b4421f615b6d76cfb400408c951fc335eeb

commit_message:
Make InstanceInfoCache load base attributes

The InstanceInfoCache object is pretty bare-bones, previously needing
only the two main attributes. Since the virt/firewall module uses
the deleted flag, we need to load that now.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects
Related to blueprint virt-objects

Change-Id: I355a20b402c5581c1582cbe321c63bab58ee4815

commit_message:
Add SecurityGroupRule object

This adds the beginnings of the SecurityGroupRule object, with
linkage back to parent and grantee groups. It is not currently
complete enough to serve as a full implementation, but provides
what we need for virt drivers.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I4099007c8d4e1c8deaa74cd001cb477a9f164261

commit_message:
Fix sqlalchemy migrations

This patch only fixes sqlalchemy migrations:
- add InnoDB engine and utf-8 for all tables,
- using of more appropriate exceptions,
- fix logic and syntax errors.

Partially implements bp: db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: Ifdc4abe06f8cd0e01e13b003ea30d1e402c9e8ba

commit_message:
Fix sqlalchemy models

This patch only makes sqlalchemy models to reflect the actual state of database

Partially implements bp: db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: I2fa2bc2f0c2b08f69bf7217dc35683d2edbedd26

As for integration tests I figured since there already backup and restore tests if I broke anything with that they would fail.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-10-25 16:37:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks for such fast response. Denis: So I just spoke with Robert who explained quotas to me (which i'm not too familiar with) and I believe I now see the problem.  I'll move the verification to the taskmanager. Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 2559, 'date': '2013-10-25 23:07:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-25 23:10:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

I believe this is better than placing the verification in taskmanager since this will not create an instance record in the db which would have occurred if I waited till the taskmanager.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-10-25 23:16:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Have you tested it on real environment?'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-10-26 18:14:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

It would be nice to see tests, when exceptions caused by backup validations and quotas are not harmed. Is it possible ?'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-10-26 18:18:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

If it is possible, please do it, it would show to all how quota works.
If not let me know.

So, finally, i'm ok with this patch, but i'd like to see more tests, thanks. Regards, Denis M."}, {'account_id': 6268, 'date': '2013-10-28 13:22:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

This looks good. Dennis, quota tests are not required as this is a change to the backup/restore logic. Moving the code outside of the _create_resources() will fix adding to any quota issues. But the fact that quotas are broken should not force us to write more tests to cover up that fact. We should instead fix quotas so that they handle errors better. At that time tests should be added to the quota tests to make sure there is no future regressions.'}, {'account_id': 694, 'date': '2013-10-28 15:58:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Dennis: Increasingly, I don't understand why Quota's is seen as broken- it seems as if most problems have stemmed from having validation steps happen outside of the function passed to the "run_with_quotas" call, or resources being provisioned outside of TaskManager. 

Anyone in this case I can't see what is going wrong with respect to quotas.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-10-28 16:02:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I didn't told that quotas is broken, i said that any raised exception inside of create_resource would cause quota rollback.And this is how qoutas work. I'm glad to see that validation moved from create_resource method.

Regards, Denis M."}, {'account_id': 694, 'date': '2013-10-28 16:37:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Dennis: Ah, ok. My apologies if I misinterpreted you.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-10-28 16:54:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Add Backup/Restore Checksum Validation

Store the swift checksum for swift storage backups. The swift checksum is
the checksum of the concatenated segment checksums.  This is the checksum
that is stored with the DB backup record so we can verify that the checksum
on restore through a swift object HEAD call.

Adds restore from backup checksum validation at API and guestagent level.
* Integrate checksum verification with check object exists at API level.
* Verify checksum right before downloading swift file.
* Verify the current swift backup file checksum matches the original backup
  checksum to prevent loading and restoring a tampered backup file.

Add swift checksum storage unit tests

Also move backup verification logic outside quotas.

Implements: blueprint verify-backup-checksum-on-restore
Change-Id: I2844cfb8a8b31f6ea7622f99eff3bea9455161e1

commit_message:
VMware: guest assisted snapshots

This implements volume_snapshot_create which creates a snapshot
of a vmdk volume. In this case prior to the snapshot the volume
needs to be consolidated and detached. Once the snapshot is
complete it will be reattached to the guest.

volume_snapshot_delete is not required as that is implemented
in the Cinder driver.

The create_snapshot API from cinderclient is used to
inform Cinder that it can go ahead and create the snapshot.

This is done using the interface added by the
blueprint qemu-assisted-snapshots.

Change-Id: I94025781aa4e11e0ce97327de5b8319104c8a96d

commit_message:
checking length of argument list in "glance-cache-image" command

Currently, "image id" is got by "pop" method without checking length
of argument list in "queue_image" method(glance/cmd/cache_manage.py)

Consequently, only last element of argument list is used,
other elements are ignored.
 ex)
  glance-cache-image queue-image <image-id1> <image-id2> <image-id3>
  -> <image-id3> is selected and queued.
     <image-id1>/<image-id2> is ignored.

Because "glance-cache-image" command is user command(*),
I think that elements which are ignored should not be existed
and checking of length is essential.

In order to check length, I replaced "try/except" statement with
"if/else" statement.

Also, I modified 2 methods at the same point.
 -delete_queued_image
 -delete_cached_image

 * http://docs.openstack.org/developer/glance/cache.html

Change-Id: I5cff1f9b5fe8f718ca74f1c9f58dba469396dc8f
Closes-Bug: #1236709

commit_message:
feat(logging): format msg when log level met

This is a feature supported by the logging module; just let the
logging function perform the formatting.

Change-Id: I9e349c6bda942474bfe73150b5abb8feb79ed574
Closes-Bug: 1232327

This patch adds shard management capability to the queues mongodb
driver.

The storage API is also correctly split into an control and data
interfaces. The data drivers are loaded by default. The control
drivers are loaded as needed by the transport layer.

commit_message:
feat: shards mongodb driver + tests

This patch adds shard management capability to the queues mongodb
driver.

The storage API is also correctly split into an control and data
interfaces. The data drivers are loaded by default. The control
drivers are loaded as needed by the transport layer.

Unit tests are also provided to verify that the driver (and future
drivers) work as expected.

Change-Id: Iad034a429a763c9a2ce161f05c928b090ab58944
Partially-implements: blueprint storage-sharding
Partially-Closes: 1241686

'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2013-10-22 16:56:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I see the usefulness of this in some cases, but not generally, and I think that if context is added to TaskManager.__init__, it should not default to None.

What would happen inside pxe.deploy.deploy() if task.context is None?  Eg, if the following, then I don't see the point in adding context...

  def deploy(self, task, node):
    ...
    if task.context:
      token = task.context.auth_token
    else:
      token = get_admin_context()

And if the following, then it should just be required...

  def deploy(self, task, node):
    ...
    if task.context:
      token = task.context.auth_token
    else:
      raise MissingContext()"}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2013-10-23 12:58:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Let's consider the following situation: keystone auth enabled, but ramdisk must POSTs info to Ironic vendor passthru API. Possible solutions:

1) Add vendor passthru to public API - not good.

2) Use auth token for ramdisk.

2a) Use Ironic token - not very good.

2b) Use token from client request.

Default to None because it not always needed for task (but needed for deploy(), I will correct commit message).

Example:

def deploy(self, task, node):
...
token = task.context.auth_token
if token:
    # auth enabled, use this token
else:
    # auth not enabled, token not needed"}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2013-10-23 13:02:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-10-23 13:02:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Yuriy,

Please give me one example where the code that instantiates TaskManager will not have a context available to it.

Unless I'm missing something, all requests will either:

b) come from a system task (eg, start() or periodic_task()) and therefor have a local admin context.

commit_message:
Add context to TaskManager

Some drivers methods can require context-specific
info. Example: keystone auth enabled, auth_token
required for deploy with use vendor_passthru in API.
Possible usage:
with task_manager.acquire(context, node_id,
                          shared=False) as task:
...
    task.driver.deploy.deploy(task, node_obj)
...

def deploy(self, task, node):
...
    token = task.context.auth_token
    if token:
...

Change-Id: Id51c005499ac4013142f71703a6aa2dca067f1ad

commit_message:
Use string selector values in Fn::Select calls

Heat changed the behavior of handling Fn::Select selector
values and no longer accepts integer values, so we should
use string ones.

ATTENTION: this should only be approved if current Heat behavior
is considered to be correct.

Closes-Bug: #1245863

Change-Id: Ie5c6f766283173e62fe057675279f17baf3dd2f0

commit_message:
Always set model = 'netfront' for xen over libvirt.

This will prevent emulated network driver to be attached to virtual machine.
Emulated network driver is not working for xen over libvirt as tap interface
name is suffixed by xen with '-emu' which makes this interface name too long.

Additionaly security groups will also not work for this interface as openstack
is setting up filters on interface without -emu suffix.

Change-Id: I0907ce148e473edf6b81ea782fac2fa6a1b71a2d
Fixes: bug #1202199

commit_message:
Check existence of directory 'lost+found'

The command `sudo rmdir $TARGET_ROOT/lost+found` will fail
if `$TARGET_ROOT/lost+found` directory doesn't exist,
e.g. when you use non-default image.

Fixes bug #1245856

Change-Id: I48c8f2f201b29912a726249023ca7d20893cc958

commit_message:
Implement /nodes/UUID/vendor_passthru in the API

The RPC and Conductor layers are already done;
this patch adds some exception handling and implements the
RPC bindings inside the API service so that /vendor_passthru
will be possible.

Change-Id: Iba3feae0445a0eb202efc5b9a346fb9931dc4b00

'}, {'account_id': 694, 'date': '2013-10-25 22:33:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Do not merge

(2 inline comments)

If you look at the current MySqlManager class, it stays fairly light and defers heavily to a MySqlAdmin and MySqlApp class. This is to avoid having the manager become a God object that has to know how to do everything the guest does.

The one exception is the prepare call which has always looked pretty gruesome and should probably be moved to its own class or module. I vote the name be something like "SystemManager." The new class should accept the initializer arguments "status" and "app" which, when used with MySQL, would be MySqlStatus and MySqlApp. 

Anyway, this has needed to happen for awhile now, and until it does I do not want to see this checks in because it leaves the yucky prepare method code not only in the manager, but promotes it to the mixin class of any potential manager.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-10-25 22:48:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)

Main point is to create some kind of mixing, because there is lots of common code between managers.'}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2013-10-25 23:48:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

2Tim: Presented review is not supposed to be a real code to merge but rather a draft/sample for hub_cap. That's what I mean by 'mixin rather then supermanager'. Just a way to decrease code duplication.
Anyway, I didn't quite get your idea. What you've written is exactly what this piece is about. Is it about 'mixin vs delegation' choice? Could u pls explain 

And +1 to Denis comments."}, {'account_id': 694, 'date': '2013-10-28 22:51:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)

@Illia Khudoshyn

I think, even before this pull request, that the prepare call should not contain so much logic. What's needed is a SystemManager class that could be responsible for both formatting / mounting volumes and setting up the application. It would do this by asking the Volume classes to work with the volumes and the App class to work with the app.

My issue is with a Mixin is that it defers to itself, implying this is class does *everything*. So it calls "_perform_restore" on itself, rather than telling the self.app class to do that. Ditto to create_user and create_database. Those are things the app class can do (even if, in the case of restore, it defers to the backup object).

If the methods such as "_perform_restore" need to change, why not make that happen in the App class, and have that be a mixin used by MySqlApp?

Over time, this design will lead to everything being put into enormous manager classes. So it feels harsh but that's why I'm -2'ing this.'}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2013-10-29 08:45:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

2 Tim Simpson:

I got it now, I guess. As I said before it was just to show my idea to Michael B. so I do not expect that you remove your -2. There is definitely a lot of work to be done.
Several thoughts though:
- I do not expect this mixin to grow, coz it supposed to only contain really common stuff
- +1 to moving volume mounting to separate class
- +1 to create_database and create_user - just forgot that to delegate to the app
- there is still 'post_prepare' hook to do all DB specific stuff on prepare
- Manager methods map to API calls directly, so eventually we will found our Manager to be aware of everything. My point was: for db specific things - to delegate, for common things - to use mixins. Now we already have a Manager delegating to an app. I would feel uncomfortable if we will have a SystemManager delegating to a Manager delegating to an App.

Thanks for your attention."}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:55:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Introduce GA manager mixin

Code, common for Managers, is extracted to a mixin.
Application and ApplicationStatus instances
accessed by Manager should be contained in Manager
instance rather then being instantiated each time
or retrieved as a singleton.

Change-Id: I35b679735f316467eb7e9f67956c4d1fab1e73e5
Implements: blueprint refactor-ga-for-other-engines-support

commit_message:
When listen_ssl is true, enable the SSL engine and set a cert/key

listen_ssl is insufficient to enable SSL because it doesn't enable
the SSL engine and doesn't set a certificate and key to use.

Change-Id: I42dc29424aee5d8abefeb26b84825daf4afa4ec7

In Python 2, an exception message is expected to be a native string (so a bytes string), not a Unicode string. str(ValueError(u'\xe9')) raises a UnicodeEncodeError for example. Exceptions are converted to native string implicitly by print for example, or explicitly using str()."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2013-10-22 15:44:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

Oh, I realized that I forgot to present myself. I am new in the OpenStack community. I am a Python core developer, I fixed a lot of Unicode related issue in Python 3 during more than 3 years on various operating systems (Windows, Mac OS X, Linux, FreeBSD, Solaris, etc.) with various locale setups.

In my experience, you should not try to get Unicode from an exception, or you will get in trouble :-)'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2013-10-23 03:52:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Oh, I just saw that sometimes OpenStack uses a text string for the exception message:
https://launchpad.net/bugs/1241877
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52726/

See my comment on the review, I proposed to add a function to Oslo to safely cast an exception to a text string.'}, {'account_id': 24, 'date': '2013-10-25 16:52:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 24, 'date': '2013-10-25 16:53:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2013-10-29 11:02:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I talked with Doug Hellmann on IRC to decide how to handle Unicode in exceptions. We agreed to pass text (Unicode) strings to exception constructors, but also to avoid implicit or explicit cast of exception to byte strings.

So the correct fix of this issue is to replace ValueError(unicode(e)) with ValueError(six.text_type(e)).

Sorry, I changed my mind, but I didn't know the strategy to port OpenStack to Python 3."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2013-10-29 11:05:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
python3: use six.text_types for unicode()

Type for representing (Unicode) textual data. This is unicode() in Python 2 and str in Python 3.

Change-Id: I8319287f3294ebf7c1a506cd4f68509d9554a5ef
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

It feels a little heavy to pull in all of werkzeug for one decorator. What other implementations were considered?"}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-10-29 13:50:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I started out with our own implementation. Then I was pointed to the Werkzeug implementation, which is much better and very fast, thanks to a certain trick. Then I looked briefly through pypi at libraries such as https://pypi.python.org/pypi/property-caching/ but I didn't find one that would use the same or equivalent technique."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:09:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with comment above.  Importing a entire library to get a 13 line decorator seems very heavy."}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:16:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

So now this patch has gone a full circle:
* I started with own code, I was pointed to better code in werkzeug,
* I copied code from werkzeug, with licenses, I was told to import it from werkzeug,
* I added werkzeug as a dependency, now it's too heavy.
At this point I see no way to use this code. I would never think that getting 13 lines of good, working code into an open source project would be so difficult."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:17:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I am not convinced that the speed up introduced by storing the property value in the parent object's __dict__ is enough justification for bringing all of werkzeug in as a dependency. The library includes far far more code that we would not be using, and that may be incompatible with other WSGI code we *do* want to use."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:19:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

If Armin gives permission, we can put the decorator in an oslo-incubator module so it can be reused by OpenStack projects. After that happens, we can consider whether it is appropriate to release it as a separate library.'}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:20:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

How is it possible for code that is not used to be incompatible?'}, {'account_id': 7680, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:20:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I don't think it's a public api, but django totally has: django.utils.functional.cached_property"}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:23:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thank you Alex, I didn't think to look into Django itself. That solves the problem, I suppose."}, {'account_id': 7680, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:24:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I checked, it's public: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.5/ref/utils/#django.utils.functional.cached_property"}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:24:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

We will use the slightly worse, but working django.utils.functional.cached_property'}]

commit_message:
Add werkzeug to global-requirements

We need to use the werkzeug.utils.cached_property decorator in horizon
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/53859/) and in tuskar-ui
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/53815/).

Change-Id: I54ff33fb237ca9d96f1cc0c31a8a8b1a92addfd5

I think adding this would solve all the concerns - but I am not sure how to deal with this and RPC versions. http://paste.openstack.org/show/45288/.

This is needed later because in _prepare_bdm - we need to update snapshots with volume ids and connection_info and whatnot - and we need the id for that. revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-16 17:33:22.000000000', 'message': "Add block device handling to build_and_run_instance

If we have block device mappings we want to prep them and pass them to
the virt driver spawn method so they can be attached to the instance.
If there's a failure during the instance creation the volumes will get
cleaned up.

A failure to prep the block devices will abort a build because it can't
be built as desired and the failure is not likely to be related to the
compute node itself.

On an instance build failure we make an attempt to clean up the block
devices for the instance.  If that fails we are left in a bad state and
will not attempt to reschedule the instance.

This is one part of a series of patches to build up the
build_and_run_instance method.

Part of bp query-scheduler

Change-Id: I4f9e3fd0b7bb443406645c1d98e673a4d3624b58

commit_message:
Add block device handling to build_and_run_instance

If we have block device mappings we want to prep them and pass them to
the virt driver spawn method so they can be attached to the instance.
If there's a failure during the instance creation the volumes will get
cleaned up.

A failure to prep the block devices will abort a build because it can't
be built as desired and the failure is not likely to be related to the
compute node itself.

On an instance build failure we make an attempt to clean up the block
devices for the instance.  If that fails we are left in a bad state and
will not attempt to reschedule the instance.

This is one part of a series of patches to build up the
build_and_run_instance method.

Part of bp remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance

Change-Id: I4f9e3fd0b7bb443406645c1d98e673a4d3624b58

python3: fix print statements

due to the fact that the print() has changed between
python2 and python3.

Change-Id: I17f3e008330952ccd5abbe02b7b16c8b893e3b7e
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

python3: use six.text_type for unicode

Use six.text_type for representing (Unicode) textual data.
This is unicode() in Python 2 and str in Python 3.

Change-Id: Ie7372dddc5ec09c2f02c0a88ae622128360db47e
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Add InstanceList.get_by_security_group()

This provides a way to get a list of instances that are in a given
security group. This alternative to SecurityGroup.instances is
much simpler and avoids the potential for passing around a
SecurityGroup object with a ton of Instance objects attached.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: Iea282ea3559da00a03121d6eff59125a5fbae0b2

commit_message:
Make security_group_rule_get_by_security_group() honor columns

This makes the above-mentioned method take a columns_to_join
parameter, which lets us control it preloading behavior.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: Ie2404633045c4ebac74225a44cbb609cf4c70887

commit_message:
Replace qpid_host with qpid_hostname

This patch replaces `qpid_host` with `qpid_hostname` in both the
documentation and the config file sample. `qpid_host` has been shipped
as the parameter to specify qpid's hostname, although the correct one is
`qpid_hostname`.

DocImpact
Closes-bug 1242715

Change-Id: I25f2d0e505560e1762f7f059728c33c47a23439e

commit_message:
Fix remove role assignment adds role using LDAP assignment

When using the LDAP assignment backend, attempting to remove a
role assignment when the role hadn't been used before would
actually add the role assignment and would not return a
404 Not Found like the SQL backend.

This change makes it so that when attempt to remove a role that
wasn't assigned then 404 Not Found is returned.

Closes-Bug: #1242855
Change-Id: I28ccd26cc4bb1a241d0363d0ab52d2c11410e8b3
(cherry picked from commit c6800ca1ac984c879e75826df6694d6199444ea0)
(cherry picked from commit b17e7bec768bd53d3977352486378698a3db3cfa)

commit_message:
Fix remove role assignment adds role using LDAP assignment

When using the LDAP assignment backend, attempting to remove a
role assignment when the role hadn't been used before would
actually add the role assignment and would not return a
404 Not Found like the SQL backend.

This change makes it so that when attempt to remove a role that
wasn't assigned then 404 Not Found is returned.

Closes-Bug: #1242855
Change-Id: I28ccd26cc4bb1a241d0363d0ab52d2c11410e8b3
(cherry picked from commit c6800ca1ac984c879e75826df6694d6199444ea0)
(cherry picked from commit b17e7bec768bd53d3977352486378698a3db3cfa)
(cherry picked from commit 4221b6020e6b0b42325d8904d7b8a22577a6acc0)

commit_message:
Optimize the scenario runner

1. Create openstack clients in the ScenarioRunner.run method, i.e. one time
   for all scenario loops (speedup);
2. Get rid of the useless Scenario.class_init() method
3. Move cleanup inside the scenario loop run to enable the cleanup
   implementations to delete the user's resources the scenario was run with;

Blueprint test-engine

Change-Id: I7f8d439baaf4a86539e6cebe7ac83d8fddcd4a47
